y 2020 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313142436/https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-eu-rules-out-schengen-border-closures-amid-italy-outbreak/a-52497811 |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-02-25/salvini-and-le-pen-don-t-have-a-european-coronavirus-cure |title=Salvini and Le Pen Don't Have a Coronavirus Cure |date=25 February 2020 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227122244/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-02-25/salvini-and-le-pen-don-t-have-a-european-coronavirus-cure |archive-date=27 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-europe-open-borders-eu-italy-france-britain-germany-spain-a9362536.html |title=Coronavirus: Europe's open borders threatened by spread of disease |date=28 February 2020 |work=The Independent |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173409/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-europe-open-borders-eu-italy-france-britain-germany-spain-a9362536.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/commission-chief-warns-against-unilateral-virus-travel-bans/ |title=Commission chief warns against unilateral virus travel bans |date=13 March 2020 |work=[[EURACTIV]] |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318195056/https://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/commission-chief-warns-against-unilateral-virus-travel-bans/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The deputy leader of the Swiss [[Ticino League]], Lorenzo Quadri, by 29 February had criticised the decision: \"It is alarming that the dogma of wide-open borders is considered a priority.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/europe/coronavirus-european-union.html |title=Coronavirus Nightmare Could Be the End for Europe's Borderless Dream |date=26 February 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303055756/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/europe/coronavirus-european-union.html |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> United States President [[Donald Trump]] said by 12 March the European Union had \"failed to take the same precautions and restrict travel from China and other hot spots\" as the US had implemented.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-trump/trump-suspends-all-travel-from-europe-to-the-united-states-to-fight-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Z04U |title=In dramatic step, Trump restricts travel from Europe to US to fight coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140433/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-trump/trump-suspends-all-travel-from-europe-to-the-united-states-to-fight-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Z04U |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy 9 March Czech Prime Minister [[Andrej Babi\u0161]] stated that \"European countries cannot ban the entry of Italian citizens within the Schengen area. The only possible way is to have the Italian prime minister call on his fellow citizens to refrain from traveling to other countries of the European Union.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.schengenvisainfo.com/news/czech-pm-italians-should-be-banned-from-travelling-due-to-coronavirus/ |title=Czech PM: Italians Should Be Banned From Travelling Due to Coronavirus |date=9 March 2020 |work=SchengenVisaInfo.com |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323171345/https://www.schengenvisainfo.com/news/czech-pm-italians-should-be-banned-from-travelling-due-to-coronavirus/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland and Denmark announced complete closure of their national borders, the [[European Commission]] President [[Ursula von der Leyen]] said by 12 March that \"Certain controls may be justified, but general travel bans are not seen as being the most effective by the World Health Organization. Moreover, they have a strong social and economic impact, they disrupt people\u2019s lives and business across the borders.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4e89ec5c-6565-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |title=Denmark, Poland and Czechs seal borders over coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |agency=Financial Times |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314202823/https://www.ft.com/content/4e89ec5c-6565-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> European Union leaders condemned the US decision to restrict travel from Europe to the United States. [[European Council]] President [[Charles Michel]] and Ursula von der Leyen said in a joint statement: \"The European Union disapproves of the fact that the US decision to impose a travel ban was taken unilaterally and without consultation.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/4552fd280d06cf83c63e4cc9b08fe5ce |title=EU condemns Trump travel ban from Europe as virus spreads |date=12 March 2020 |work=Associated Press (AP) |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313140528/https://apnews.com/4552fd280d06cf83c63e4cc9b08fe5ce |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ursula von der Leyen admitted by 17 March that \"all of us who are not experts initially underestimated the coronavirus.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/news/politicians-underestimated-virus-threat-von-der-leyen-admits/ |title=Politicians 'underestimated' virus threat, von der Leyen admits |date=18 March 2020 |work=Euractiv |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319152350/https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/news/politicians-underestimated-virus-threat-von-der-leyen-admits/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Italian government has criticised EU's lack of solidarity with Italy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-eu-abandoning-italy-china-aid/ |title=The EU Is Abandoning Italy in Its Hour of Need |date=14 March 2020 |work=Foreign Policy |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315112947/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-eu-abandoning-italy-china-aid/ |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/italy-criticises-eu-being-slow-help-coronavirus-epidemic |title=Italy criticises EU for being slow to help over coronavirus epidemic |date=11 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313000621/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/italy-criticises-eu-being-slow-help-coronavirus-epidemic |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3bc25ea-652c-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |title=Italy wonders where Europe's solidarity is as coronavirus strains show |date=13 March 2020 |work=Financial Times |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315154437/https://www.ft.com/content/d3bc25ea-652c-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-12/Italy-calls-for-extra-help-for-COVID-19-only-China-responded--ONp6w2rmvu/index.html |title=Italy criticizes EU for not responding its call for help, 'only China responded bilaterally' |date=12 March 2020 |work=CGTN |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316024124/https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-12/Italy-calls-for-extra-help-for-COVID-19-only-China-responded--ONp6w2rmvu/index.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Politico'' reported on 7 March that \"EU countries have so far refused Italy's plea for help fighting coronavirus, as national capitals worry that they may need to stockpile face masks and other medical gear to help their own citizens, officials and diplomats said.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-aims-better-control-coronavirus-responses/ |title=Europe fails to help Italy in coronavirus fight |date=7 March 2020 |work=Politico |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317055659/https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-aims-better-control-coronavirus-responses/ |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Maurizio Massari, Italy's ambassador to the EU, said that \"Only China responded bilaterally. Certainly, this is not a good sign of European solidarity.\"<ref name=\"politico-corona\" /> [[Serbia]]n President [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]] said that \"European solidarity does not exist. That was a fairy tale.\"<ref name=\"politico-corona\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-china-winning-propaganda-war/ |title=China is winning the coronavirus propaganda war |date=18 March 2020 |work=Politico |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322203919/https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-china-winning-propaganda-war/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe planned [[NATO]] \u201c[[List of NATO exercises|Defender 2020]]\u201d military exercise in Germany, Poland, and the Baltic states,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/how-coronavirus-derailed-the-largest-nato-exercise-in-25-years |title=How coronavirus derailed the largest Nato exercise in 25 years |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Spectator |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325102257/https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/how-coronavirus-derailed-the-largest-nato-exercise-in-25-years |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> the largest NATO war manoeuvres since the end of the [[Cold War]], was to be held on a reduced scale because of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nato/nato-scales-down-exercises-due-to-coronavirus-idUSKBN21627V |title=NATO scales down exercises due to coronavirus |date=19 March 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325102254/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nato/nato-scales-down-exercises-due-to-coronavirus-idUSKBN21627V |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]]'s general secretary [[Kate Hudson (activist)|Kate Hudson]] critisiced the Defender 2020 exercise: \"In the current public-health crisis, it jeopardises the lives not only of the troops from the US and the many European countries participating but the inhabitants of the countries in which they are operating.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/nato-must-end-dangerous-and-irresponsible-military-exercise-on-russias-border-campaigners-say |title=Nato must end 'dangerous and irresponsible' military exercise on Russia's border, campaigners say |date=18 March 2020 |work=Morning Star |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320010441/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/nato-must-end-dangerous-and-irresponsible-military-exercise-on-russias-border-campaigners-say |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[PREPARE]] (EU PREPARE project)\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"OKOpress_Szumowski_EU_claims\">{{cite news | last1= Pa\u0144kowska | first1= Maria | language =pl | title= Szumowski krytykuje UE: 'Nie ma tej europejskiej solidarno\u015bci'. To wielopi\u0119trowy fa\u0142sz |trans-title = Szumowski criticise the EU: 'There is no European solidarity'. Which is false at many levels<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-26 |newspaper= [[OKO.press]] | url= https://oko.press/szumowski-krytykuje-ue-nie-ma-tej-europejskiej-solidarnosci-to-wielopietrowy-falsz/ |quote= Bo jak by\u015bmy czekali na inne kraje, na Europ\u0119, na \u015bwiat, to by\u015bmy si\u0119 obudzili bez \u015brodk\u00f3w, a dooko\u0142a wszyscy by te \u015brodki sobie zakupili ... \u017beby by\u0142a jasno\u015b\u0107, to nie jest tak, \u017ce my ten sprz\u0119t mamy w Europie, \u017ce s\u0105 jego nieograniczone ilo\u015bci. ... Bo niestety tutaj centralne zakupy zawiod\u0142y, nie ma tej europejskiej solidarno\u015bci.  |accessdate=2020-03-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200326225848/https://oko.press/szumowski-krytykuje-ue-nie-ma-tej-europejskiej-solidarnosci-to-wielopietrowy-falsz/ |archivedate= 2020-03-26 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/ ncov \u2013 CSSE] - Map of the expansion of the virus in Europe and in the world\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Europe|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Europe]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by continent|Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ondoro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics by country", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe"}
{"title_page": "Markt Schwaben station", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name                = {{\u00d6PNV M\u00fcnchen|S|20}} Markt Schwaben\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = de\n| symbol              = \n| symbol2             = \n| symbol_location     = de\n| type                = \n| image               = Markt Schwaben, Bahnhof, 2.jpeg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| other_name          = \n| address             = Bahnhofstr. 36<br>85570 [[Markt Schwaben]]\n| borough             = [[Bavaria]]\n| country             = [[Germany]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|48.193268|11.861900|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation           = <!-- {{convert|0|m|abbr=on}} -->\n| owned               = [[Deutsche Bahn]]\n| operator            = {{Plainlist|1=\n*[[DB Netz]]\n*[[DB Station&Service]]\n}}\n| line                = [[Munich\u2013M\u00fchldorf railway]]<br>[[Markt Schwaben\u2013Erding railway]]\n| distance            = \n| platforms           = 2\n| tracks              = 4\n| train_operators     = [[S-Bahn M\u00fcnchen]]<br>[[S\u00fcdostbayernbahn]]\n| connections         = {{\u00d6PNV M\u00fcnchen|BUS}}\n| code                = {{Deutsche Bahn station codes|code=3971|ds100=MSB<ref name=Eisenbahnatlas >{{cite book|title=Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland (German railway atlas) | edition=2009/2010 |publisher= Schweers + Wall | year= 2009 |isbn= 978-3-89494-139-0}}</ref>|ibnr=8003879|category=3<ref name =categories >{{DBCatsURL}}</ref>}}\n| zone                = {{\u00d6PNV M\u00fcnchen|MVV}}: 2 and 3<ref>{{cite web |title=S-Bahn, U-Bahn, Regionalzug, Tram und ExpressBus im MVV |url=https://www.mvv-muenchen.de/fileadmin/mediapool/03-Plaene_Bahnhoefe/Netzplaene/MVV_Netzplan_S_U_R_T_X.pdf |publisher=[[M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund]] |accessdate=28 February 2020 |date=December 2019}}</ref>\n| architect           = \n| architectural_style = \n| opened              = {{Start date|1871|5|1|df=y}}\n| closed              = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| passengers          = \n| pass_year           = \n| website             = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/Markt_Schwaben.html www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type            = Bavaria#Germany#Europe\n| map_caption         = Location in Bavaria##Location in Germany##Location in Europe\n| map_dot_label       = Markt Schwaben\n| embedded            = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-colour       = #C60C30\n| stroke-width        = 3\n| marker              = rail-underground\n| marker-colour       = #009D58\n| zoom                = 15\n}}\n| services            = \n{{s-rail|title=S\u00fcdostbayernbahn}}\n{{s-line|system=RB|line=|type=M\u00fcnchen|type2=M\u00fchldorf|previous=M\u00fcnchen Ost|next=H\u00f6rlkofen}}\n{{s-line|system=RB|line=|type=M\u00fcnchen|type2=Simbach am Inn|previous=M\u00fcnchen Ost|next=H\u00f6rlkofen}}\n{{s-rail|title=MSB}}\n{{s-line|system=MSB|line=S2|previous=Poing|next=Ottenhofen}}\n| other_services      = \n{{s-rail|title=M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund{{!}}MVV-Regionalbus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=446|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Hallenbad}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=463|previous=Markt Schwaben, Burgerfeld|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=469|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=505|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=507|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=568|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Anwesen Hechtl}}\n{{s-rail|title=M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund{{!}}MVV-RufTaxi}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=5050|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=5680|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Anwesen Hechtl}}\n}}\n\n'''Markt Schwaben station''' is a [[railway station]] on the [[Munich S-Bahn]] in the municipality of [[Markt Schwaben]] in the northeast area of [[Munich]], [[Germany]]. It is served by the [[Munich S-Bahn|S-Bahn]] line {{MSB lines|S2}}.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Munich\u2013M\u00fchldorf railway]] was taken in operation on 1 May 1871.<ref name=\"Wanka p. 10\">{{citation|surname1=Reinhard Wanka, Wolfgang Wiesner|title=Die Hauptbahn M\u00fcnchen\u2013Simbach und ihre Zweigbahnen|publisher=Bufe-Fachbuch-Verlag|publication-place=Egglham|isbn=3-922138-59-4|date=1996|language=German|pages=10\n}}</ref> Subsequently, the municipality of [[Erding]] also tried for a railway connection, this could be opened on 16 November 1872.<ref name=\"Wanka p. 42\">{{citation|surname1=Reinhard Wanka, Wolfgang Wiesner|title=Die Hauptbahn M\u00fcnchen\u2013Simbach und ihre Zweigbahnen|publisher=Bufe-Fachbuch-Verlag|publication-place=Egglham|isbn=3-922138-59-4|date=1996|language=German|pages=42\n}}</ref> In 1970, the [[Markt Schwaben\u2013Erding railway]] and [[Munich\u2013M\u00fchldorf railway]] (Munich-Markt Schwaben section) was electrified to introduce a S-Bahn operation on these lines. In 1972, with the establishment of the [[Munich S-Bahn]] system, Markt Schwaben was better connected, including by the connection to [[Munich]] through the [[M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund]].<ref name=\"B\u00fcrger p. 156, 178\">{{citation|surname1=Karl B\u00fcrger|title=M\u00fcnchen\u2013M\u00fchldorf\u2013Simbach. Glanz, Niedergang und Renaissance einer k\u00f6niglich bayerischen Eisenbahn. Bewegte Verkehrsgeschichte mit umw\u00e4lzender Zukunft|publication-place=Walpertskirchen|isbn=978-3-00-056474-1|date=2017|language=German|pages=156, 178\n}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px>\nFile:MS bridge.JPG|Footbridge in the southwestern part of the station.\n</gallery>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Munich Airport rail services}}\n{{Portal bar|Transport|Germany}}\n{{Munich transport network}}\n\n[[Category:Munich S-Bahn stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1871]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ebersberg (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| name                = {{\u00d6PNV M\u00fcnchen|S|20}} Markt Schwaben\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = de\n| symbol              = \n| symbol2             = \n| symbol_location     = de\n| type                = \n| image               = Markt Schwaben, Bahnhof, 2.jpeg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| other_name          = \n| address             = Bahnhofstr. 36<br>85570 [[Markt Schwaben]]\n| borough             = [[Bavaria]]\n| country             = [[Germany]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|48.193268|11.861900|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation           = <!-- {{convert|0|m|abbr=on}} -->\n| owned               = [[Deutsche Bahn]]\n| operator            = {{Plainlist|1=\n*[[DB Netz]]\n*[[DB Station&Service]]\n}}\n| line                = [[Munich\u2013M\u00fchldorf railway]]<br>[[Markt Schwaben\u2013Erding railway]]\n| distance            = \n| platforms           = 2\n| tracks              = 4\n| train_operators     = [[S-Bahn M\u00fcnchen]]<br>[[S\u00fcdostbayernbahn]]\n| connections         = {{\u00d6PNV M\u00fcnchen|BUS}}\n| code                = {{Deutsche Bahn station codes|code=3971|ds100=MSB<ref name=Eisenbahnatlas >{{cite book|title=Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland (German railway atlas) | edition=2009/2010 |publisher= Schweers + Wall | year= 2009 |isbn= 978-3-89494-139-0}}</ref>|ibnr=8003879|category=3<ref name =categories >{{DBCatsURL}}</ref>}}\n| zone                = {{\u00d6PNV M\u00fcnchen|MVV}}: 2 and 3<ref>{{cite web |title=S-Bahn, U-Bahn, Regionalzug, Tram und ExpressBus im MVV |url=https://www.mvv-muenchen.de/fileadmin/mediapool/03-Plaene_Bahnhoefe/Netzplaene/MVV_Netzplan_S_U_R_T_X.pdf |publisher=[[M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund]] |accessdate=28 February 2020 |date=December 2019}}</ref>\n| architect           = \n| architectural_style = \n| opened              = {{Start date|1871|5|1|df=y}}\n| closed              = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| passengers          = \n| pass_year           = \n| website             = [https://www.bahnhof.de/bahnhof-de/Markt_Schwaben.html www.bahnhof.de]\n| map_type            = Bavaria#Germany#Europe\n| map_caption         = Location in Bavaria##Location in Germany##Location in Europe\n| map_dot_label       = Markt Schwaben\n| embedded            = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-colour       = #C60C30\n| stroke-width        = 3\n| marker              = rail-underground\n| marker-colour       = #009D58\n| zoom                = 15\n}}\n| services            = \n{{s-rail|title=S\u00fcdostbayernbahn}}\n{{s-line|system=RB|line=|type=M\u00fcnchen|type2=M\u00fchldorf|previous=M\u00fcnchen Ost|next=H\u00f6rlkofen}}\n{{s-line|system=RB|line=|type=M\u00fcnchen|type2=Simbach am Inn|previous=M\u00fcnchen Ost|next=H\u00f6rlkofen}}\n{{s-rail|title=MSB}}\n{{s-line|system=MSB|line=S2|previous=Poing|next=Ottenhofen}}\n| other_services      = \n{{s-rail|title=M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund{{!}}MVV-Regionalbus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=446|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Hallenbad}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=463|previous=Markt Schwaben, Burgerfeld|next=}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=469|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=505|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=507|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=568|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Anwesen Hechtl}}\n{{s-rail|title=M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund{{!}}MVV-RufTaxi}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=5050|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Rathaus}}\n{{s-line|system=MVV|line=5680|previous=|next=Markt Schwaben, Anwesen Hechtl}}\n}}\n\n'''Markt Schwaben station''' is a [[railway station]] on the [[Munich S-Bahn]] in the town of [[Markt Schwaben]] in the northeast area of [[Munich]], [[Germany]]. It is served by the [[Munich S-Bahn|S-Bahn]] line {{MSB lines|S2}}.\n\n==History==\nThe [[Munich\u2013M\u00fchldorf railway]] was taken in operation on 1 May 1871.<ref name=\"Wanka p. 10\">{{citation|surname1=Reinhard Wanka, Wolfgang Wiesner|title=Die Hauptbahn M\u00fcnchen\u2013Simbach und ihre Zweigbahnen|publisher=Bufe-Fachbuch-Verlag|publication-place=Egglham|isbn=3-922138-59-4|date=1996|language=German|pages=10\n}}</ref> Subsequently, the municipality of [[Erding]] also tried for a railway connection, this could be opened on 16 November 1872.<ref name=\"Wanka p. 42\">{{citation|surname1=Reinhard Wanka, Wolfgang Wiesner|title=Die Hauptbahn M\u00fcnchen\u2013Simbach und ihre Zweigbahnen|publisher=Bufe-Fachbuch-Verlag|publication-place=Egglham|isbn=3-922138-59-4|date=1996|language=German|pages=42\n}}</ref> In 1970, the [[Markt Schwaben\u2013Erding railway]] and [[Munich\u2013M\u00fchldorf railway]] (Munich-Markt Schwaben section) was electrified to introduce a S-Bahn operation on these lines. In 1972, with the establishment of the [[Munich S-Bahn]] system, Markt Schwaben was better connected, including by the connection to [[Munich]] through the [[M\u00fcnchner Verkehrs- und Tarifverbund]].<ref name=\"B\u00fcrger p. 156, 178\">{{citation|surname1=Karl B\u00fcrger|title=M\u00fcnchen\u2013M\u00fchldorf\u2013Simbach. Glanz, Niedergang und Renaissance einer k\u00f6niglich bayerischen Eisenbahn. Bewegte Verkehrsgeschichte mit umw\u00e4lzender Zukunft|publication-place=Walpertskirchen|isbn=978-3-00-056474-1|date=2017|language=German|pages=156, 178\n}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px>\nFile:MS bridge.JPG|Footbridge in the southwestern part of the station.\n</gallery>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Munich Airport rail services}}\n{{Portal bar|Transport|Germany}}\n{{Munich transport network}}\n\n[[Category:Munich S-Bahn stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1871]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Bavaria]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Ebersberg (district)]]\n", "name_user": "Flummi-2011", "label": "safe", "comment": "corr.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markt_Schwaben_station"}
{"title_page": "1. FC Schweinfurt 05", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = 1. FC Schweinfurt 05\n| fullname    = 1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905, Verein f\u00fcr Leibes\u00fcbungen e.V.\n| image       = 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 logo.svg\n| image_size  = 200\n| nickname    = ''Die Schn\u00fcdel'' <br> ''Die Gr\u00fcn-Wei\u00dfen''\n| founded     = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1905|5|5}}\n| ground      = [[Willy-Sachs-Stadion]]\n| capacity    = 15,060<ref name=\"Stadion\">{{cite web|title=Schweinfurter DFB-Pokalspiel ausverkauft|trans-title=DFB-Pokal match sold out|publisher=www.bfv.de|url=http://www.bfv.de/cms/spielbetrieb/neuigkeiten/news_archiv_85656_schweinfurter_dfb-pokalspiel_ausverkauft_223856.html|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=German}}</ref> (860 seated)\n| chairman    = Markus Wolf\n| manager     = Tobias Strobl\n| league      = [[Regionalliga Bayern]] (IV)\n| season      = [[2018\u201319 Regionalliga|2018\u201319]]\n| position    = 4th\n| current     = \n| website     = http://www.fcschweinfurt05.de/\n| pattern_la1 =\n| pattern_b1  =\n| pattern_ra1 =\n| pattern_sh1 =\n| pattern_so1 =\n| leftarm1    = 228B22\n| body1       = 228B22\n| rightarm1   = 228B22\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = 228B22\n| pattern_la2 =\n| pattern_b2  =\n| pattern_ra2 =\n| pattern_sh2 =\n| pattern_so2 =\n| leftarm2    = 000000\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = 000000\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| socks2      = AAFF00\n| pattern_la3 =\n| pattern_b3  =\n| pattern_ra3 =\n| pattern_sh3 =\n| pattern_so3 =\n| leftarm3    =\n| body3       =\n| rightarm3   =\n| shorts3     =\n| socks3      =\n}}\n'''1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905, Verein f\u00fcr Leibes\u00fcbungen e.V.''', called '''1. FC Schweinfurt 05''',  '''Schweinfurt 05''', or simply '''FC 05''', is a [[football in Germany|German association football club]] established in [[Schweinfurt]] ([[Bavaria]]) in 1905. It has sections for [[netball]], [[fistball]], [[field hockey]], [[badminton]], [[gymnastics]], [[Rugby football|rugby]], [[American football]], [[futsal]], and [[Sport of athletics|athletics]].\n\nThe club is well-known nationally and even internationally due to successful years in top and second tier football leagues from the 1930s to the 1970s. During the late 1930s, Schweinfurt's [[midfielder]]s [[Albin Kitzinger]] and [[Andreas Kupfer]], today considered as two of the best [[Half back (association football)|half-back]] players of all time,<ref name=\"Wunderteam\">{{cite web|title=Breslau Elf Chronicles \u2013 Tale Of A German Wunderteam |publisher=www.thehardtackle.com|url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2012/breslau-elf-chronicles-tale-of-a-german-wunderteam/ |accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Schnuedel\">{{cite web|title=Eintracht gegen Schweinfurt: Wer sind diese Schn\u00fcdel \u00fcberhaupt? |publisher=www.fnp.de|url=https://www.fnp.de/eintracht-frankfurt/eintracht-gegen-schweinfurt-sind-diese-schnuedel-ueberhaupt-10447715.html|accessdate=27 November 2019|language=German}}</ref> \nformed the core of the [[Germany national football team]] and represented their country at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup]] and within the [[FIFA]] selection [[Europe XI]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Football Association 75th Anniversary Celebration Match: England 3 Rest of Europe 0 |publisher=www.englandfootballonline.com|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1938-39/M0220RoE1938.html |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1. FC Schweinfurt 05 |publisher=www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de | url=https://www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de/vereine/sportvereine/1-fc-schweinfurt-1905/ |accessdate=19 July 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe FC 05 first team, which competes in the tier-four [[Regionalliga Bayern]] since the [[2013\u201314 Regionalliga|2013\u201314]] season, is organized within ''1. FC Schweinfurt 1905 Fu\u00dfball GmbH''.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=1. FC Schweinfurt 05: Geschichte|trans-title=1. FC Schweinfurt 05: History|publisher=www.fcschweinfurt05.de|url=http://www.fcschweinfurt1905.de/geschichte/|accessdate=17 June 2017|language=German}}</ref> The club plays its home games at [[Willy-Sachs-Stadion]] in Schweinfurt.<ref name=\"Willy Sachs Stadion\">{{cite web|title=Willy-Sachs-Stadion Schweinfurt|publisher=www.youtube.de|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QkUqXTzCubo&t=92s/|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early years: 1905\u20131931===\n[[File:Schweinfurt 1905 First Team.jpg|thumb|280px|right|1. FC Schweinfurt 05 team in 1905]]\n\nAt a time when football became more and more popular among broad levels of the population, ''1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905'' was founded on 5 May 1905 by a group of sports enthusiasts. The club's first chairman Pepi Popp designed the still unchanged FC 05 crest.<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\"/> \n\nThe team played in the local leagues until beginning of the [[First World War]]. Back  then, the home games were held at [[Stadion am Hutrasen|Hutrasen]] south of river [[Main (river)|Main]], which later became the venue of local competitor [[VfR 07 Schweinfurt]]. In 1919, Schweinfurt 05 had to move to a new court near Ludwigsbr\u00fccke and became member of the tier-one [[Kreisliga Bayern|Kreisliga Nordbayern]], but relegated after its first season. The team attempted a merger with Turngemeinde Schweinfurt von 1848, which lasted from 1921 to 1923, before the two groups parted ways again and the football division became ''1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905, Verein f\u00fcr Leibes\u00fcbungen e.V.''<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nWhile FC 05 did not reap the expected benefits from the brief union, it improved dramatically after re-establishing itself as an independent club. Membership grew significantly and a number of new sports departments were formed within the organization. The football team yielded its first fruits in 1927 by winning the Unterfranken Cup championship,<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\">{{cite web|title=Geschichte des FC 05 Schweinfurt | trans-title=FC Schweinfurt 05 History|publisher=www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de | url=https://www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de/geschichte/geschichte-des-fc-05-schweinfurt/ |accessdate=26 July 2017|language=German}}</ref> and in 1931, when it became Kreisliga Unterfranken champion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kreisliga Bayern 1931|trans-title=1931 Kreisliga Bayern|publisher=fussball-historie.de|url=http://www.fussball-historie.de/Sued/OstkreisII1931.html|accessdate=10 April 2020|language=German}}</ref>\n\n===Years of excellence: 1931\u20131963===\n[[File:Andreas Kupfer and Albin Kitzinger.jpg|thumb|280px|right|[[Andreas Kupfer]] (left) and [[Albin Kitzinger]]]]\n\nSchweinfurt 05 finally gained first class status again with its entry into the [[Bezirksliga Bayern]] in 1931. \nAfter introduction of the [[Gauliga]] system in 1933, the club became member of the top-flight [[Gauliga Bayern]]. \nSchweinfurt had a couple of successful seasons in this era, winning the Gauliga Bayern in [[1938\u201339 Gauliga Bayern|1939]] and [[1941\u201342 Gauliga Bayern|1942]], and qualifying for the [[List of German football champions|German football championship]] round.\n \nIn the German football championship [[1939 German football championship|1939]] competition, the team barely missed the semi-final qualification games after 3 wins in the group stage, where it defeated later [[1943 German football championship|1943]] and [[1944 German football championship|1944]] German champion [[Dresdner SC]] 1\u20130 in the first leg, but then lost to Dresden 0\u20131 in the deceisive away match.<ref name=\"Stumpf\">{{cite web|title=Ehemaliger 05-Torwart Hans Stumpf gestorben|trans-title=Former 05 goalkeeper Hans Stumpf passed|publisher=mainpost.de|url=https://www.mainpost.de/sport/schweinfurt/Ehemaliger-05-Torwart-Hans-Stumpf-gestorben;art795,5487291?wt_ref=https%3A%2F%2Fde.wikipedia.org%2F&wt_t=1585256396531|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=German}}</ref>\nThe club failed in the round of 16 of the [[1942 German football championship|1942]] German football championship after a 1\u20132 loss to [[SG SS Stra\u00dfburg]].\n\nSchweinfurt made a semi-final appearance in the [[1936 Tschammerpokal]], when it was defeated 2\u20133 by [[FC Schalke 04]], the closest it ever came to winning a national title. Again in 1936, the club moved into its newly constructed stadium, the [[Willy-Sachs-Stadion]], a donation by local [[ZF Sachs|industrialist]] and patron [[Willy Sachs]].<ref name=\"Cicero\">{{cite web|title=Der braune Schatten|trans-title=The brown shadow|publisher=cicero.de|url=http://cicero.de/wirtschaft/der-braune-schatten/37229|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\nAt that time, FC 05 midfielders [[Albin Kitzinger]] and [[Andreas Kupfer|Andreas 'Ander' Kupfer]] became renowned in international football as they formed one of the best half-back duos in Europe. Kitzinger and Kupfer were an essential part of the famous [[Breslau Eleven|Germany national team]] who defeated [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] 8\u20130 in [[Wroc\u0142aw|Breslau]] ([[Poland]]) on 16 May 1937.<ref name=\"Wunderteam\"/> One year later they competed at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup]], and were both called up to represent Germany within the FIFA selection [[Europe XI]] in the [[The Football Association|FA]] 75th anniversary game against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Highbury Stadium|Highbury]] in [[London]].\n\nDue to the [[Second World War]], Schweinfurt 05 merged with Luftwaffen SV Schweinfurt into KSG Schweinfurt for the [[1943\u201344 Gauliga Bayern|1943\u201344]] and [[1944\u201345 Gauliga Bayern|1944\u201345]] Gauliga seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gauligisten| trans-title=Gauliga clubs|publisher=www.deutscherfussball.info | url=https://www.deutscherfussball.info/Gauligisten-S-d--Sa_Se.htm |accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> The club temporarily had been dissolved in May 1945 under pressure from the occupying powers.<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\"/>\n\nAfter World War II, the re-established 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 was integrated into the first tier [[Oberliga S\u00fcd (1945\u201363)|Oberliga S\u00fcd]], which, for the first time in German football, introduced the system of contract players in August 1948.<ref>{{cite web|title=Der lange Weg zum Profi| trans-title=The long road to professional football|publisher=www.bpb.de | url=https://www.bpb.de/gesellschaft/medien-und-sport/bundesliga/160779/geschichte-der-bundesliga?p=1 |accessdate=11 April 2020|language=German}}</ref>  \nThe club stayed in the Oberliga for the duration of the league's existence until the [[Bundesliga]], Germany's new professional league, was founded in 1963. \nSchweinfurt reached the round of the last sixteen of the [[DFB-Pokal 1954\u201355|1954\u201355]] DFB-Pokal, where it lost 0\u20131 in the replay against FC Schalke 04 after a 1\u20131 draw in the first match.\nOn the occasion of the club's 50th anniversary in 1955, Schweinfurt could demonstrate its level when the team defeated German champion [[Rot-Weiss Essen]] 3\u20131, and achieved a 1\u20131 draw against [[Everton F.C.]] from English [[Football League First Division]].<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\"/>\n\nIn 1950, Andreas Kupfer became the first [[Captain (sports)|captain]] of the [[West Germany]] national football team on the occasion of his very final [[List of Germany international footballers|44th]] appearance. FC 05 goalkeeper [[G\u00fcnter Bernard]] made two West Germany appearances in 1962, before he joined Bundesliga founding member [[SV Werder Bremen]] one year later, and was named in Germany's squad for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n===Second tier years: 1963\u20131976===\nAs it did not qualify for the newly established Bundesliga in 1963, Schweinfurt 05 found itself playing in the second tier [[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1963\u20131974)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]. In the [[1965\u201366 Regionalliga|1965\u201366]] season, the club became Southern German champion and made it to the [[1965\u201366 Regionalliga#Bundesliga promotion round|Bundesliga advancement games]], but was unable to ascend to the top tier.\n\nWith the introduction of the [[2. Bundesliga]] in 1974, Schweinfurt was founding member of the [[2. Bundesliga S\u00fcd (1974\u201381)|southern division]] despite only finishing 15th in the last Regionalliga year. For its first 2. Bundesliga season in [[1974\u201375 2. Bundesliga|1974\u201375]], the club had signed-up former national team [[forward (association football)|striker]] and [[List of Bundesliga top scorers|Bundesliga top scorer]] [[Lothar Emmerich]]. The team earned an excellent third place and barely missed the advancement games for promotion to Bundesliga.\n\n===Yo-yo years: 1976\u20132016===\n[[File:Schweinfurt Performance Chart.png|280px|thumb|Historical chart of the 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 league performance after 1945]]\nAfter the 1974\u201375 season, FC 05 began to falter: poor results and financial problems saw the club descend first to the [[Bayernliga]] (III) and then, for the first time in 1983, to the [[Landesliga Bayern-Nord]] (IV). Schweinfurt 05 became a [[yo-yo club]] ascending and descending between tiers III and IV, with just a pair of brief 2. Bundesliga appearances in [[1990\u201391 2. Bundesliga|1990\u201391]] and in [[2001\u201302 2. Bundesliga|2001\u201302]]. In the [[1989\u201390 DFB-Pokal|1989\u201390]] season the team made it into the last sixteen of the [[DFB-Pokal]], where it lost 0\u20132 to [[Eintracht Braunschweig]].\n\nDisasters happened in 2004 when FC Schweinfurt 05 was forced to leave the Regionalliga S\u00fcd (III) because of financial reasons, and in 2005 when the club went bankrupt. The results in the Bayernliga (IV) were annulled and the team was relegated to the fifth tier Landesliga.\n\nA re-structured club successfully worked its way back into Bayernliga in 2008. After it was relegated again to the Landesliga in 2009, the team returned to the Bayerliga immediately the following year. At the end of the [[2011\u201312 Bayernliga|2011\u201312]] season the club managed to qualify for the promotion round to the new [[Regionalliga Bayern]] (IV) and advanced to the second round, where the club missed out on promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Das war die Relegation 2012 auf Verbandsebene |publisher=www.fupa.net|url=http://www.fupa.net/berichte/so-laeuft-die-relegation-auf-verbandsebene-21714.html |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe club finally earned direct promotion to tier-four Regionalliga Bayern in the [[2012\u201313 Bayernliga|2012\u201313]] season by taking the championship in the Bayernliga northern division.\nSchweinfurt's first three Regionalliga years, however, were characterized by a permanent struggle against relegation.\nFC Schweinfurt 05 finished the [[2013\u201314 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2013\u201314]] Regionalliga with a relegation play-off rank only courtesy of a controversial final game of the season. The team turned a 1\u20133 deficit into a 4\u20133 win with three goals in the last four minutes of the game,<ref>{{cite web|title='Skandal': Emp\u00f6rung nach Schweinfurts Aufholjagd |publisher=www.kicker.de|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/regionalliga/startseite/605098/artikel_skandal_empoerung-nach-schweinfurts-aufholjagd.html |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref> and successfully defended its league place in the following relegation round. The club again managed to avoid relegation only very tightly during the following two seasons.\n\n===Recent years: 2016\u2013today===\n[[File:2018-08-17 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 vs. FC Schalke 04 (DFB-Pokal) by Sandro Halank\u2013100.jpg|thumb|280px|[[2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal]]: [[Nabil Bentaleb]] ([[FC Schalke 04]]) and [[Adam Jabiri]] (FC Schweinfurt 05)]]\nIn 2016, the FC 05 first team was spun off into ''1. FC Schweinfurt 1905 Fu\u00dfball GmbH''. By means of the reorganization, the club again established professional structures that shall pave the way back to higher leagues.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Legende: 1. FC Schweinfurt 05|trans-title=A legend: 1. FC Schweinfurt 05|url=http://www.zeitspiel-magazin.de/legende-1-fc-schweinfurt-05.html|publisher=zeitspiel-magazin.de|language=German|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\nSchweinfurt actually experienced an upturn in the [[2016\u201317 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2016\u201317]] season and finished 8th in Regionalliga Bayern. In addition, the team succeeded in winning the [[Bavarian Cup]] after a 1\u20130 victory over [[SV Wacker Burghausen]] in the final, combined with qualification for the [[2017\u201318 DFB-Pokal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Schweinfurt 05 gewinnt den Toto-Pokal 2017|trans-title=Schweinfurt 05 has won the 2017 Toto Cup|publisher=bfv.de|url=http://www.bfv.de/cms/spielbetrieb/neuigkeiten/2017_205893_schweinfurt_gewinnt_den_toto-pokal_2017_215550.html|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2017\u201318]] Regionalliga, Schweinfurt's ambitioned team was not able to jeopardize the championship of [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]], which had been relegated directly from 2. Bundesliga to Regionalliga Bayern after the [[2016\u201317 2. Bundesliga|2016\u201317]] season due to a missing license for [[3. Liga]]. The club finally finished 3rd, where striker [[Adam Jabiri]] became 2017\u201318 Regionalliga Bayern top scorer (28 goals). \n1. FC Schweinfurt 05 defeated 2. Bundesliga club [[SV Sandhausen]] 2\u20131 in the 2017\u201318 DFB-Pokal first round,<ref>{{cite web|title=DFB-Pokal, 2017/2018, 1. Runde|publisher=www.dfb.de|url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal/spieltag/?spieledb_path=%2Fmatches%2F2247860 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> but then lost 0\u20134 to later [[2018 DFB-Pokal Final|cup winner]] [[SG Eintracht Frankfurt]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DFB-Pokal, 2017/2018, 2. Runde|publisher=www.dfb.de|url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal/spieltag/?spieledb_path=%2Fmatches%2F2249085 |accessdate=25 October 2017|language=German}}</ref>\nIn the same season, Schweinfurt 05 successfully defended the [[2017\u201318 Verbandspokal|Bavarian Cup]] after a 3\u20131 victory over league competitor [[SpVgg Oberfranken Bayreuth]] in the final, and qualified for the [[2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal]].\n\nWith the objective of the [[2018\u201319 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2018\u201319 Regionalliga]] championship and promotion to 3. Liga, Schweinfurt signed up former [[2009 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|European U-17 Champion]] [[Florian Trinks]]. \nHowever, the club clearly missed the chance for promotion and finished 4th end of this season.\nIn the 2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal first round, Schweinfurt lost 0\u20132 to [[2017\u201318 Bundesliga|previous season's Bundesliga runner-up]] and [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League]] competitor [[FC Schalke 04]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DFB-Pokal, 2018/2019, 1. Runde|publisher=www.dfb.de|url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal/spieltag/?no_cache=1&spieledb_path=%2Fmatches%2F2261348 |accessdate=18 August 2018|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=DFB Cup Men: 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 vs. FC Schalke 04 |publisher=tv.dfb.de|url=https://tv.dfb.de/video/dfb-cup-men-1-fc-schweinfurt-05-vs-fc-schalke-04/22518/ |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===League===\n* '''[[Gauliga Bayern]]''' (I)\n** '''Champions''': (2) [[1938\u201339 Gauliga Bayern|1938\u201339]], [[1941\u201342 Gauliga Bayern|1941\u201342]]\n** ''Runners-up'': (2) [[1936\u201337 Gauliga Bayern|1936\u201337]], [[1942\u201343 Gauliga Bayern|1942\u201343]]<sup>\u2020</sup>\n* '''[[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1963\u20131974)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]''' (II)* (III)**\n** '''Champions''': [[1965\u201366 Regionalliga|1965\u201366]]*\n** ''Third'': [[2000\u201301 Regionalliga|2000\u201301]]**<sup>\u2021</sup>\n* '''[[Bayernliga]]''' (III)* (IV)**\n** '''Champions''': (2) 1989\u201390*<sup>\u2021</sup>, 1997\u201398**\n** ''Runners-up'': (2) 1981\u201382*, 1988\u201389*\n* '''[[Bayernliga|Bayernliga Nord]]''' (V)\n** '''Champions''': 2012\u201313\n* '''[[Landesliga Bayern-Nord]]''' (IV)* (V)** (VI)***\n** '''Champions''': (3) 1983\u201384*, 1985\u201386*, 2006\u201307**\n** ''Runners-up'': 2009\u201310***\n* '''[[Landesliga Bayern-Nordwest]]''' (VI)\n** '''Champions''': 2016\u201317<sup>#</sup>\n===Youth===\n* '''[[Bavarian Under 19 championship]]'''\n** '''Winners''': 2001\n** ''Runners-up'': (3) 1961, 1966, 1968\n* '''[[Bavarian Under 17 championship]]'''\n** '''Winners''': 2005\n** ''Runners-up'': 1995\n* '''[[Bavarian Under 15 championship]]'''\n** '''Winners''': 2003\n** ''Runners-up'': (2) 1986, 1994\n{{col-2}}\n===Cup===\n* '''[[DFB-Pokal]]'''\n** ''Semi-finals'': [[Tschammerpokal 1936|1936]]\n** ''Last sixteen'': (2) [[DFB-Pokal 1954\u201355|1954\u201355]], [[DFB-Pokal 1989\u201390|1989\u201390]]\n* '''Southern German Cup'''\n** '' Runners-up'': (3) 1933, 1957, 1958\n* '''[[Bavarian Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners''': (3) 1933, [[2016\u201317 Verbandspokal|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Verbandspokal|2017\u201318]]\n* '''[[Bavarian Cup#Regional winners|Unterfranken Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners''': (5) 1927, 1963<sup>#</sup>, 1996, [[2006 Bavarian Cup|2006]], [[2009 Bavarian Cup|2009]]\n<br>\n<sup>\u2020</sup> Northern division <br> <sup>\u2021</sup> Promoted to [[2001\u201302 2. Bundesliga|2. Bundesliga]] <br> <sup>#</sup> Reserve team\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Seasons==\n===First team===\nThe season-by-season performance of the club from 1931 until today:<ref>{{cite web|title=Das deutsche Fu\u00dfball-Archiv | trans-title=Historical German domestic league tables|publisher=www.f-archiv.de | url=http://www.f-archiv.de/ |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fussball.de&nbsp;\u2013 Ergebnisse | trans-title=Tables and results of all German football leagues|publisher=www.fussball.de | url=http://www.fussball.de/fussball-ergebnisse-die-top-ligen-bei-fussball-de/id_45692854/index |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\n{| border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=2>\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#dfdfdf\"\n| '''Season'''\n| '''Division'''\n| '''[[Bavarian football league system|Tier]]'''\n| '''Position'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1931\u201332\n| align=\"left\"| [[Bezirksliga Bayern | Bezirksliga Bayern (Nord)]]\n| rowspan=32| I\n| 4th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1932\u201333\n| align=\"left\"| Bezirksliga Bayern (Nord)\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1933\u201334 Gauliga Bayern|1933\u201334]]\n| align=\"left\"| [[Gauliga Bayern]]\n| 4th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1934\u201335 Gauliga Bayern|1934\u201335]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1935\u201336 Gauliga Bayern|1935\u201336]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 4th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1936\u201337 Gauliga Bayern|1936\u201337]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 2nd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1937\u201338 Gauliga Bayern|1937\u201338]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1938\u201339 Gauliga Bayern|1938\u201339]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 1st\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1939\u201340 Gauliga Bayern|1939\u201340]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1940\u201341 Gauliga Bayern|1940\u201341]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1941\u201342 Gauliga Bayern|1941\u201342]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 1st\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1942\u201343 Gauliga Bayern|1942\u201343]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Nordbayern\n| 2nd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1943\u201344 Gauliga Bayern|1943\u201344]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Nordbayern\n| 5th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1944\u201345 Gauliga Bayern|1944\u201345]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| ''no results''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1945\u201346 Oberliga|1945\u201346]]\n| align=\"left\"| [[Oberliga S\u00fcd (1945\u201363)|Oberliga S\u00fcd]]\n| 7th\