{"title_page": "Big Girls Don't Cry (The Sopranos)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Big Girls Don't Cry (''The Sopranos'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = Big Girls Don't Cry\n| series = [[The Sopranos]]\n| season = 2\n| episode = 5\n| guests= ''see below''\n| airdate = February 13, 2000\n| length = 51 minutes\n| production = 205\n| writer = [[Terence Winter]]\n| director = [[Tim Van Patten]]\n| photographer = [[Phil Abraham]]\n| episode_list = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 2)\n| image = Sopranos ep205.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| prev = [[Commendatori]]\n| next = [[The Happy Wanderer (The Sopranos)|The Happy Wanderer]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Big Girls Don't Cry'''\" is the eighteenth episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and is the fifth of the show's second season. It was written by [[Terence Winter]], directed by [[Tim Van Patten]] and originally aired on February 13, 2000.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]]\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Pussy Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]]\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]]\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]] *\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]]\n* [[David Proval]] as [[Richie Aprile]]\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Livia Soprano]] *\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n* [[Jerry Adler]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Hesh Rabkin|Hesh Rabkin]]\n* [[Kathrine Narducci]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Charmaine Bucco|Charmaine Bucco]]\n* [[John Ventimiglia]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Artie Bucco|Artie Bucco]]\n\n====Also guest starring====\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Peter Bogdanovich]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Elliot Kupferberg|Dr. Elliot Kupferberg]]\n* [[Linda Emond]] as Dahlia\n* [[Louis Lombardi]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]]\n* [[Oksana Lada]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Irina Peltsin|Irina Peltsin]]\n* [[Federico Castelluccio]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Furio Giunta|Furio]]\n* [[Vincent Curatola]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#John \"Johnny Sack\" Sacrimoni|Johnny Sack]]\n* [[Steve R. Schirripa]] as [[Bobby Baccalieri]]\n* John Fiore as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Soprano crime family|Gigi Cestone]]\n* Stephen Payne as Dominic\n* Lydia Gaston as Rosie\n* Sasha Nesterov as Russian Man\n* Elena Antonenko as Russian Woman\n* Oni Faida Lampley as Cynthia\n* Scott Lucy as Acting Student\n* [[Ajay Naidu]] as Omar\n* [[Robert Prescott (actor)|Robert Prescott]] as Mitch\n* [[Phyllis Somerville]] as Brenda\n}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Adriana La Cerva|Adriana]] is proud of [[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]]'s screenwriting and encourages it. For his birthday, she enrolls him in an \"Acting for Playwrights\" course. He is applauded for his acting, especially an emotional scene in which he plays a son with his father. When a student asks him how he managed to cry, he walks out, troubled and embarrassed. In the next lesson, playing another scene with the student who played his father, he snaps. He hits him hard, and kicks him as he lies on the floor. At home that night, he throws away everything he has written.\n\n[[List of The Sopranos characters#Furio Giunta|Furio Giunta]] is now in [[New Jersey]], a [[soldato|soldier]] with the [[Soprano family|Soprano crime family]]. Christopher has been making collections from the owner of a massage parlor/brothel but has not been using enough pressure, and the payments are short. [[Tony Soprano|Tony]] sends Furio instead. He ruthlessly assaults customers and girls, breaks the owner's arm and shoots him in the kneecap, and hits his wife and spits on her.\n\nWith Furio's arrival, Tony raises [[Paulie Gualtieri|Paulie]] and [[Silvio Dante|Silvio]] in status, and lowers [[List of The Sopranos characters#Salvatore \"Big Pussy\" Bonpensiero|Pussy]]. Pussy complains about this betrayal, as he sees it, to Agent [[List of The Sopranos characters#Agent Skip Lipari|Lipari]], who feels he has been passed over in his job as well. Sympathizing with each other, each complains about the declining standards of his own organization.\n\nTony is getting short-tempered and violent. He is inflamed when he learns that [[Janice Soprano|Janice]] is negotiating a loan, using their mother's house as security. He goes there early one morning to confront her. He is taken aback when the door is opened by [[List of The Sopranos characters#Richie Aprile|Richie]], who says that he and Janice have revived the relationship they had many years ago. Tony says that their relationship was like Israel and Palestine. He leaves, saying with disgust, \"She's your fucking problem now.\"\n\nTony visits [[List of The Sopranos characters#Hesh Rabkin|Hesh Rabkin]], seeking the comfort and guidance from him that he is not getting from [[Jennifer Melfi|Dr. Melfi]]. Hesh is sympathetic, and tells Tony that [[List of The Sopranos characters#Soprano crime family|his father]] also had panic attacks. However, Hesh does not want to hear Tony's dreams and gets bored; in response to Tony's troubles he remembers his own experiences, and rambles on about them.\n\nDr Melfi consults [[List of The Sopranos characters#Elliot Kupferberg|Dr. Kupferberg]], and tries to understand her feelings about her gangster client. Eventually, she decides to take him back. At their first session, while questions are being asked and answered, it seems they cannot stop smiling at each other.\n\n==Title reference==\n* The episode's title is taken from the name of a [[Big Girls Don't Cry (The Four Seasons song)|song]] by [[The Four Seasons (band)|Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]], which can be heard in the background during the restaurant scene in the episode. Valli would later have a role on the series as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Rusty Millio|Rusty Millio]].\n\n== Music ==\n*The song played in the background of Artie's restaurant is the titular song of the episode, \"[[Big Girls Don't Cry (The Four Seasons song)|Big Girls Don't Cry]]\" by [[The Four Seasons (band)|Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]].\n*The song playing when Christopher enters the massage parlor is \"[[Touch It (Monifah song)|Touch It]]\" by [[Monifah]].\n*The song from Dr. Melfi's dream about Tony Soprano is \"[[Optimistic Voices]]\", a selection from the 1939 film classic, ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''.\n*The song played during Furio's party is \"[[Rock the Boat (The Hues Corporation song)|Rock the Boat]]\" by [[The Hues Corporation]].\n*The song played over the end credits is \"White Mustang II\" by [[Daniel Lanois]].\n\n== Filming locations ==\nListed in order of first appearance:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sopranos-locations.com/season-2/episode-5/|title=The Sopranos location guide - Filming locations for|last=Ugoku|website=www.sopranos-locations.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* [[Kearny, New Jersey]]\n* [[Lou Costello]] Memorial in [[Paterson, New Jersey]]\n* [[Long Island City|Long Island City, Queens]]\n* [[Verona, New Jersey]]\n* [[Glen Head, New York]]\n* [[Great Kills, Staten Island]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/index.html#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/18-big-girls-dont-cry/index.html \"Big Girls Don't Cry\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705230|Big Girls Don't Cry}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/big-girls-dont-cry-26465|Big Girls Don't Cry}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Girls Don't Cry}}\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2000 American television episodes]]\n\n[[fr:Cas de conscience (Les Soprano)]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Big Girls Don't Cry (''The Sopranos'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = Big Girls Don't Cry\n| series = [[The Sopranos]]\n| season = 2\n| episode = 5\n| guests= ''see below''\n| airdate = February 13, 2000\n| length = 51 minutes\n| production = 205\n| writer = [[Terence Winter]]\n| director = [[Tim Van Patten]]\n| photographer = [[Phil Abraham]]\n| episode_list = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 2)\n| image = Sopranos ep205.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| prev = [[Commendatori]]\n| next = [[The Happy Wanderer (The Sopranos)|The Happy Wanderer]]\n}}\n\n\"'''Big Girls Don't Cry'''\" is the eighteenth episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and is the fifth of the show's second season. It was written by [[Terence Winter]], directed by [[Tim Van Patten]] and originally aired on February 13, 2000.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]]\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Pussy Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]]\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]]\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]] *\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]]\n* [[David Proval]] as [[Richie Aprile]]\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Livia Soprano]] *\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n* [[Jerry Adler]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Hesh Rabkin|Hesh Rabkin]]\n* [[Kathrine Narducci]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Charmaine Bucco|Charmaine Bucco]]\n* [[John Ventimiglia]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Artie Bucco|Artie Bucco]]\n\n====Also guest starring====\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Peter Bogdanovich]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Elliot Kupferberg|Dr. Elliot Kupferberg]]\n* [[Linda Emond]] as Dahlia\n* [[Louis Lombardi]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]]\n* [[Oksana Lada]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Irina Peltsin|Irina Peltsin]]\n* [[Federico Castelluccio]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Furio Giunta|Furio]]\n* [[Vincent Curatola]] as [[List of The Sopranos characters#John \"Johnny Sack\" Sacrimoni|Johnny Sack]]\n* [[Steve R. Schirripa]] as [[Bobby Baccalieri]]\n* John Fiore as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Soprano crime family|Gigi Cestone]]\n* Stephen Payne as Dominic\n* Lydia Gaston as Rosie\n* Sasha Nesterov as Russian Man\n* Elena Antonenko as Russian Woman\n* Oni Faida Lampley as Cynthia\n* Scott Lucy as Acting Student\n* [[Ajay Naidu]] as Omar\n* [[Robert Prescott (actor)|Robert Prescott]] as Mitch\n* [[Phyllis Somerville]] as Brenda\n}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Adriana La Cerva|Adriana]] is proud of [[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]]'s screenwriting and encourages it. For his birthday, she enrolls him in an \"Acting for Playwrights\" course. He is applauded for his acting, especially an emotional scene in which he plays a son with his father. When a student asks him how he managed to cry, he walks out, troubled and embarrassed. In the next lesson, playing another scene with the student who played his father, he snaps. He hits him hard, and kicks him as he lies on the floor. At home that night, he throws away everything he has written.\n\n[[List of The Sopranos characters#Furio Giunta|Furio Giunta]] is now in [[New Jersey]], a [[soldato|soldier]] with the [[Soprano family|Soprano crime family]]. Christopher has been making collections from the owner of a massage parlor/brothel but has not been using enough pressure, and the payments are short. [[Tony Soprano|Tony]] sends Furio instead. He ruthlessly assaults customers and girls, breaks the owner's arm and shoots him in the kneecap, and hits his wife and spits on her.\n\nWith Furio's arrival, Tony raises [[Paulie Gualtieri|Paulie]] and [[Silvio Dante|Silvio]] in status, and lowers [[List of The Sopranos characters#Salvatore \"Big Pussy\" Bonpensiero|Pussy]]. Pussy complains about this betrayal, as he sees it, to Agent [[List of The Sopranos characters#Agent Skip Lipari|Lipari]], who feels he has been passed over in his job as well. Sympathizing with each other, each complains about the declining standards of his own organization.\n\nTony is getting short-tempered and violent. He is inflamed when he learns that [[Janice Soprano|Janice]] is negotiating a loan on their mother's house as security. He goes to the house early one morning to confront her. He is taken aback when the door is opened by [[List of The Sopranos characters#Richie Aprile|Richie]], who says that he and Janice have revived the relationship they had many years ago. Tony says that their relationship was like Israel and Palestine. He leaves, saying with disgust, \"She's your fucking problem now.\"\n\nTony visits [[List of The Sopranos characters#Hesh Rabkin|Hesh Rabkin]], seeking the comfort and guidance from him that he is not getting from [[Jennifer Melfi|Dr. Melfi]]. Hesh is sympathetic, and tells Tony that [[List of The Sopranos characters#Soprano crime family|his father]] also had panic attacks. However, Hesh does not want to hear Tony's dreams and gets bored; in response to Tony's troubles he remembers his own experiences, and rambles on about them.\n\nDr Melfi consults [[List of The Sopranos characters#Elliot Kupferberg|Dr. Kupferberg]], and tries to understand her feelings about her gangster client. Eventually, she decides to take him back. At their first session, while questions are being asked and answered, it seems they cannot stop smiling at each other.\n\n==Title reference==\n* The episode's title is taken from the name of a [[Big Girls Don't Cry (The Four Seasons song)|song]] by [[The Four Seasons (band)|Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]], which can be heard in the background during the restaurant scene in the episode. Valli would later have a role on the series as [[List of The Sopranos characters#Rusty Millio|Rusty Millio]].\n\n== Music ==\n*The song played in the background of Artie's restaurant is the titular song of the episode, \"[[Big Girls Don't Cry (The Four Seasons song)|Big Girls Don't Cry]]\" by [[The Four Seasons (band)|Frankie Valli and the Four Seasons]].\n*The song playing when Christopher enters the massage parlor is \"[[Touch It (Monifah song)|Touch It]]\" by [[Monifah]].\n*The song from Dr. Melfi's dream about Tony Soprano is \"[[Optimistic Voices]]\", a selection from the 1939 film classic, ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''.\n*The song played during Furio's party is \"[[Rock the Boat (The Hues Corporation song)|Rock the Boat]]\" by [[The Hues Corporation]].\n*The song played over the end credits is \"White Mustang II\" by [[Daniel Lanois]].\n\n== Filming locations ==\nListed in order of first appearance:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sopranos-locations.com/season-2/episode-5/|title=The Sopranos location guide - Filming locations for|last=Ugoku|website=www.sopranos-locations.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n* [[Kearny, New Jersey]]\n* [[Lou Costello]] Memorial in [[Paterson, New Jersey]]\n* [[Long Island City|Long Island City, Queens]]\n* [[Verona, New Jersey]]\n* [[Glen Head, New York]]\n* [[Great Kills, Staten Island]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/index.html#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/18-big-girls-dont-cry/index.html \"Big Girls Don't Cry\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705230|Big Girls Don't Cry}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/big-girls-dont-cry-26465|Big Girls Don't Cry}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Girls Don't Cry}}\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2000 American television episodes]]\n\n[[fr:Cas de conscience (Les Soprano)]]\n", "name_user": "April 31st", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSynopsis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Girls_Don%27t_Cry_(The_Sopranos)"}
{"title_page": "Lorde", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|New Zealand singer and songwriter}}\n{{about|the singer|other uses|Lorde (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|Lordi|Lord (disambiguation){{!}}Lord}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Lorde\n| image           = RF 3006 Lorde@Arena Krists Luhaers-5 (35769377251) (cropped).jpg\n| alt             = Lorde performing onstage against a purple background\n| caption         = Lorde performing in June 2017\n| birth_name      = Ella Marija Lani Yelich-O'Connor\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1996|11|7}}\n| birth_place     = [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n| citizenship     = {{hlist|New Zealand|[[Croatia]]}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|record producer}}<!---occupation(s) artist is notable for, \"as given in the lead\", per: [[Template:Infobox_person#Parameters]]--> \n| years_active    = 2009\u2013present\n| relatives      = [[Sonja Yelich]] (mother)\n| awards          = [[List of awards and nominations received by Lorde|Full list]]\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = <!-- Sourced in #Musical style. Please do not add or remove genres without discussion or reliable sources -->{{hlist|[[Electropop]]|[[dream pop]]|[[indie pop]]|[[art pop]]|<!-- See talk page before editing this -->}}\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Joel Little]]|[[Jack Antonoff]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Universal Music Group|UMG]]|[[Lava Records|Lava]]|[[Republic Records|Republic]]}}\n| website         = {{url|lorde.co.nz}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ella Marija Lani Yelich-O'Connor''' (born 7 November 1996), known professionally as '''Lorde''' (pronounced \"lord\"), is a New Zealand singer and songwriter.<!--only occupations integral to artist's notability per reliable sources; [[MOS:LEADBIO]]--> Taking inspiration from [[aristocracy (class)|aristocracy]] for her stage name, she is known for employing unconventional musical styles and thoughtful songwriting. Born in the [[Auckland]] suburb of [[Takapuna]] and raised in neighbouring [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]], Lorde expressed interest in performing at local venues in her early teens. She signed with [[Universal Music Group]] in 2009 and collaborated with producer [[Joel Little]] in 2011 to start recording material.\n\nUniversal Music commercially released the pair's first collaborative effort, an [[extended play]] (EP) titled ''[[The Love Club EP|The Love Club]]'', in 2013. The EP's international chart-topping single \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\" helped Lorde rise to prominence. Her debut studio album ''[[Pure Heroine]]'' followed that year and achieved critical and commercial success. The following year, Lorde curated [[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1 (soundtrack)|the soundtrack]] for the 2014 film ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay&nbsp;\u2013 Part 1|The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1]]'' and recorded several tracks, including the single \"[[Yellow Flicker Beat]]\". Her second studio album ''[[Melodrama (Lorde album)|Melodrama]]'' (2017) garnered widespread acclaim and debuted at number one in the United States.\n\nLorde's music is primarily [[electropop]] and contains elements of [[Music genres|subgenres]] such as [[dream pop]] and [[indie-electro]]. [[List of awards and nominations received by Lorde|Her accolades]] include two [[Grammy Awards]], two [[Brit Awards]] and a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination. She appeared in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s list of the most influential teenagers in 2013 and 2014, and the 2014 edition of [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 Under 30]]. In addition to her solo work, she has co-written songs for other artists, including [[Broods]] and [[Bleachers (band)|Bleachers]]. As of June 2017, Lorde has sold over five million albums worldwide.\n\n==Early life==\nElla Marija Lani Yelich-O'Connor was born in [[Takapuna]], [[Auckland]] on 7 November 1996,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehairpin.com/2014/01/here-is-lordes-birth-certificate/|title=Here Is Lorde's Birth Certificate|website=[[The Hairpin]]|date=28 January 2014|first=Emma|last=Carmichael|accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> to poet [[Sonja Yelich]] ({{lang-hr|Sonja Jeli\u0107}}) and civil engineer Vic O'Connor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1847971/lorde-parents-engaged/|title=Lorde's Parents Finally Got Engaged&nbsp;\u2013 After 30 Years|first=Brenna|last=Ehrlich|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=17 June 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> Her mother was born to [[Croats|Croatian]] immigrants from the region of [[Dalmatia]], while her father is of Irish descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/21869-singer-lorde-talks-croatian-heritage|title=Grammy Award Winner Lorde Talks Croatian Heritage|website=Total-croatia-news.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818052331/https://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/21869-singer-lorde-talks-croatian-heritage|archivedate=18 August 2018}}</ref> They announced their engagement in 2014, after a 30-year relationship,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rothman |first1=Michael |title=Lorde's Parents Engaged, at Last |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/lordes-parents-engaged/story?id=24171630 |accessdate=20 August 2019 |work=ABC News |date=17 June 2014}}</ref> and in 2017, they married in a private ceremony in [[Cheltenham, New Zealand|Cheltenham Beach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://i.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/92299673/lordes-parents-get-married-in-auckland|title=Lorde's parents get married in Auckland|work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nSecond of four children, she has three siblings: older sister Jerry, younger sister India, and younger brother Angelo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lorde's younger sister makes musical debut|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/lordes-younger-sister-makes-musical-debut-20140121-315t0.html|accessdate=25 January 2014|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=21 January 2014}}</ref> They were raised in the nearby Auckland suburb of [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]].<ref name=\"CoverStory\"/> At age five, she joined a drama group and developed [[public speaking]] skills.<ref name=\"Weiner\" /> As a child, Lorde attended [[Vauxhall School]] and then [[Belmont Intermediate School]] in her early teens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/north-shore-times/8990736/Singer-now-on-centre-stage|title=Singer now on centre stage: Shore kid makes good at Splendour in the Grass|date=2 August 2013|first=Jess|last=Etheridge|work=North Shore Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053757/http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/north-shore-times/8990736/Singer-now-on-centre-stage|archivedate=21 September 2013}}</ref> Her mother encouraged her to read a range of genres, which Lorde cited as a lyrical influence. More specifically, she cites the [[young adult literature|young adult]] [[dystopian]] novel ''[[Feed (Anderson novel)|Feed]]'' (2002) by [[Matthew Tobin Anderson|M.T. Anderson]] as well as authors [[J.D. Salinger]], [[Raymond Carver]] and [[Janet Frame]] for influencing her songwriting.<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\">{{cite web|title=Lorde, the year|work=Black Magazine|first=Grant|last=Fell|url=http://www.blackmagazine.co.nz/blk-list/lorde-the-year/|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10433978/Lorde-interview-Dream-Teen.html|title=Lorde interview: Dream Teen|author=McNulty, Bernadette|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=8 November 2013|accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2009\u20132011: Beginnings===\n[[File:Ella Yelich O'Connor.png|thumb|upright|Lorde performing at the Victoria Theatre in Devonport, 2011|alt=A black-and-white photo of Lorde performing. She is seen touching her hair and smiling while looking downwards]]\n\nIn May 2009, Lorde and her friend Louis McDonald won the Belmont Intermediate School annual talent show as a duo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/lorde-returns-to-belmont-intermediate-school-to-judge-talent-show/story-fni0b8dw-1226761816655|title=Lorde returns to Belmont Intermediate School to judge talent show|work=[[Herald Sun]]|date=17 November 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/76Dfyut0H?url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/lorde-returns-to-belmont-intermediate-school-to-judge-talent-show/news-story/fd9f2d49397cd63a45031e9f245da8e8|archivedate=16 February 2019|access-date=17 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In August that year, Lorde and McDonald made a guest appearance on [[Jim Mora (broadcaster)|Jim Mora]]'s ''Afternoons'' show on [[Radio New Zealand]]. There, they performed [[cover version|covers]] of [[Pixie Lott]]'s \"[[Mama Do (Uh Oh, Uh Oh)]]\" and [[Kings of Leon]]'s \"[[Use Somebody]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Ella Yelich-O'Connor|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/national/programmes/afternoons/audio/2033420/ella-yelich-o%27connor|publisher=Radio New Zealand|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=17 March 2011}}</ref> McDonald's father then sent his recordings of the duo covering \"Mama Do\" and [[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]]'s \"[[Warwick Avenue (song)|Warwick Avenue]]\" to [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG)'s [[A&R]] executive Scott Maclachlan.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> Maclachlan subsequently signed her to UMG for development.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/>\n\nLorde was also part of the Belmont Intermediate School band Extreme; the band placed third in the North Shore Battle of the Bands finals at the Bruce Mason Centre, Takapuna, Auckland on 18 November 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/lorde-at-age-12-performing-with-her-middle-school-band/|title=Watch 12-Year-Old Lorde Wow Crowd with Her Middle School Band|last=Bender|first=Kelli|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=2 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009092853/https://people.com/celebrity/lorde-at-age-12-performing-with-her-middle-school-band/|archivedate=9 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Lorde and McDonald formed a duet called \"Ella & Louis\" and performed covers live on a regular basis at local venues, including caf\u00e9s in Auckland and the Victoria Theatre in Devonport.<ref name=\"Brunt\">{{cite book|title=Made in Australia and Aotearoa/New Zealand: Studies in Popular Music|first1=Shelley|last1=Brunt|first2=Geoff|last2=Stahl|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2018|isbn=978-1-317-270-478|page=72}}</ref> In 2011, UMG hired vocal coach [[Frances Dickinson]] to give her singing lessons twice a week for a year.<ref name=\"lordevmusic\"/> During this time, Maclachlan attempted to partner Lorde with several different producers and songwriters, but without success.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_ScottM.html|title=Interview with Scott MacLachlan, manager of Lorde|publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=21 January 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q1NyPMHr?url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_ScottM.html|archivedate=2 June 2014|first=Jan|last=Blumentrath|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Stuff.co.NZ:newestPop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/culture/performance/8654143/Lorde-NZs-newest-pop-star|title=NZ newest pop star|date=10 May 2013|first=Tom|last=Cardy|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> As she began writing songs, she learned how to \"put words together\" by reading [[short fiction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-young-lordes-royal-tour-1394049175|title=A Young Lorde's Royal Tour|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|first=Jim|last=Fusilli|date=5 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009092846/https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-young-lordes-royal-tour-1394049175|archivedate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nLorde performed her original songs for the first time at the Victoria Theatre in November 2011.<ref name=\"Brunt\"/> In December, Maclachlan paired Lorde with [[Joel Little]], a songwriter, record producer, and former [[Goodnight Nurse]] lead singer. The pair recorded five songs for an [[extended play]] (EP) at Little's Golden Age Studios in [[Morningside, Auckland]], and finished within three weeks.<ref name=\"NZMusician\">{{cite journal|url=https://nzmusician.co.nz/features/joel-little-rings-of-the-lorde/|title=Joel Little&nbsp;\u2013 Rings of the Lorde|first=Richard|last=Thorne|journal=NZ Musician|date=October\u2013November 2013|volume=17|issue=9|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref> While working on her music career, she attended [[Takapuna Grammar School]] from 2010 to 2013, completing [[Year Twelve#New Zealand|Year 12]].<ref name=\"behindsuccess\">{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/89970537/from-devonport-to-diva-the-story-of-lorde-so-far|title=From Devonport to diva: The story of Lorde so far|date=3 March 2017|work=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> She later chose not to return in 2014 to attend [[Year Thirteen#New Zealand|Year 13]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/234418/she's-still-our-lorde,-say-friends|title=She's still our Lorde, say friends|publisher=Radio New Zealand|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u20132015: ''Pure Heroine'' and ''The Hunger Games'' soundtrack===\n[[File:Lorde - Coachella 2014 (06).jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Lorde wears a white crop top and black trousers singing onstage while closing her eyes.|Lorde at the [[Coachella Festival]] in 2014]]\n\nWhen Lorde and Little had finished their first collaborative effort, ''[[The Love Club EP]]'', Maclachlan applauded it as a \"strong piece of music\", but worried if the EP could profit because Lorde was obscure at the time.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> In November 2012, the singer self-released the EP through her [[SoundCloud]] account for free download.<ref name=\"CoverStory\"/> UMG commercially released ''The Love Club'' in March 2013 after it had been downloaded 60,000 times, which signaled that Lorde had attracted a range of audiences.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Qz78eMoL?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/8653616/Lorde-A-Kiwi-music-mystery|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/8653616/Lorde-A-Kiwi-music-mystery|title=Lorde: A Kiwi music mystery|first=Tom|last=Cardy|work=Stuff.co.nz|date=10 May 2013|archivedate=11 July 2014}}</ref> It peaked at number two in New Zealand and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Lorde&titel=The+Love+Club+EP&cat=s|title=The Love Club EP|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\", the EP's single, helped Lorde rise to prominence after it became a critical and commercial success, selling more than 10 million units worldwide.<ref name=\"royalties\">{{cite news|last=Nippert|first=Matt|date=7 November 2014|title=Birthday girl Lorde's earnings estimated at $11m-plus|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11354524|url-status=live|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730020806/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11354524|archivedate=30 July 2018}}</ref> It charted at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making Lorde, then 16 years old, the youngest artist to earn a number-one single in the United States since [[Tiffany Darwish|Tiffany]] in 1987,<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/10/04/lorde-is-youngest-performer-to-top-billboard-charts-in-26-years/|title=Lorde is Youngest Performer to Top Billboard Charts in 26 Years|first=Tim|last=Newcomb|date=4 October 2013|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref> and has since been certified [[RIAA certification|diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2018/06/13/there-are-now-over-20-singles-that-have-been-certified-diamond/#3e4d374db4ed|title=There Are Now Over 20 Singles That Have Been Certified Diamond|first=Hugh|last=McIntyre|work=[[Forbes]]|date=13 June 2018|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> The track won two [[Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|56th ceremony]].<ref name=\"2014Grammys\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/01/26/showbiz/grammys-winners-list/index.html|title=Grammys 2014: Winners list|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=27 January 2014|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nLorde's debut studio album ''[[Pure Heroine]]'' containing the single \"Royals\" was released in September 2013 to critical acclaim;<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> it appeared on several year-end album lists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dietz|first1=Jason|title=Music Critic Top 10 Lists|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-ten-albums-of-2013|accessdate=8 January 2018|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|date=4 December 2013}}</ref> The album received considerable attention for its portrayal of suburban teenage disillusionment and critiques of mainstream culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/18614-lorde-pure-heroine/|title=Lorde: Pure Heroine {{!}} Album Reviews|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|first=Lindsay|last=Zoladz|date=3 October 2013|accessdate=8 September 2014}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/06/26/on-melodrama-lorde-learns-how-messy-adulthood-can-be|title=On 'Melodrama', Lorde Learns How Messy Adulthood Can Be|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=26 June 2017|accessdate=1 February 2019|first=Carrie|last=Battan}}<br />{{cite web|first=Joe|last=Zadeh|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/lorde-pure-heroine|title=Lorde&nbsp;\u2013 Pure Heroine &#124; Reviews|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> In the United States, the album exceeded sales of one million copies in February 2014, becoming the first debut album by a female artist since [[Adele]]'s ''[[19 (Adele album)|19]]'' (2008) to achieve the feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5922997/lordes-pure-heroine-hits-1-million-in-sales |title=Lorde's 'Pure Heroine' Hits 1 Million in Sales |work=Billboard |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304061926/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5922997/lordes-pure-heroine-hits-1-million-in-sales|archivedate=4 March 2014|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=28 February 2014}}</ref> ''Pure Heroine'' earned a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]],<ref name=\"2014Grammys\"/> and has sold four million copies worldwide as of May 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shah |first=Neil |title=Lorde Wonders How Much Fame is Enough |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/lorde-wonders-how-much-fame-is-enough-1494347686 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=9 May 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Three other singles were released from the album: \"[[Tennis Court (song)|Tennis Court]]\" reached number one in New Zealand,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2215|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> while \"[[Team (Lorde song)|Team]]\" charted at number six in the United States,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5915783/pharrell-williams-happy-hits-no-1-on-hot-100 |title=Pharrell Williams' 'Happy' Hits No. 1 On Hot 100 |work=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> and \"[[Glory and Gore]]\" was released exclusively to US radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2014/03/01/lordes-glory-gore-confirmed-next-single/|title=Lorde's 'Glory and Gore' Confirmed As Next Single|website=Headline Planet|date=1 March 2014|first=Brian|last=Cantor|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Lorde signed a publishing deal with [[Songs Music Publishing]], worth a reported US$2.5&nbsp;million, after a bidding war between companies including [[Sony Music Entertainment]] and her label UMG. The agreement gave the publisher the right to license Lorde's music for films and advertising.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Hampp|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/5785900/lorde-signs-25-million-deal-with-songs-music-publishing-inside-the-lengthy|title=Lorde Signs $2.5 Million Deal with Songs Music Publishing: Inside the Lengthy Bidding War|work=Billboard|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Later that month, Lorde was featured on the [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013), performing a cover of [[Tears for Fears]]' 1985 song \"[[Everybody Wants to Rule the World]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunger Games: Catching Fire soundtrack features Coldplay, Lorde and Christina Aguilera |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/10443307/Hunger-Games-Catching-Fire-soundtrack-features-Coldplay-Lorde-and-Christina-Aguilera.html |accessdate=8 February 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 November 2013}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included her on their lists of the most influential teenagers in the world in 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://time100.time.com/2013/11/12/the-16-most-influential-teens-of-2013/|title=Lorde, 17 {{!}} The 16 Most Influential Teens of 2013|journal=Time|first=Mark|last=Metcalfe|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3486048/most-influential-teens-2014/|title=The 25 Most Influential Teens of 2014|date=13 October 2014|work=Time|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' also placed her on their 2014 edition of [[Forbes 30 Under 30|30 Under 30]]; she was the youngest individual to be featured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/eeel45ehgfg/lorde-17/|title=Lorde, 17|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' featured her on their 21 Under 21 list in 2013,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lipshutz |first1=Jason |title=6. Lorde: 21 Under 21 (2013) |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/5721561/lorde-21-under-21-2013 |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=25 September 2013}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lipshutz |first1=Jason |title=1. Lorde: 21 Under 21 (2014) |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/6244245/lorde-21-under-21-2014 |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=10 September 2014}}</ref> and 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Partridge |first1=Kenneth |title=Billboard's 21 Under 21 2015: Music's Hottest Young Stars |url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/6745079/billboard-21-under-21-2015-hottest-young-stars |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=30 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2014, Lorde performed at festivals including the [[St Jerome's Laneway Festival|Laneway Festival]] in Sydney,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/laneway-festival-in-sydney-gave-us-lorde-and-felt-just-right-20140203-31w22.html|title=Laneway Festival in Sydney gave us Lorde and felt just right|first=Bernard|last=Zuel|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=3 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203175430/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/laneway-festival-in-sydney-gave-us-lorde-and-felt-just-right-20140203-31w22.html|archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref> the three South American editions of [[Lollapalooza]]\u2014[[Lollapalooza Chile|Chile]],<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102012134/http://cnnchile.com/noticia/2013/11/01/este-es-el-line-up-definitivo-de-lollapalooza-chile-2014-encabezado-por-arcade-fire-y-red-hot-chili-peppers|url=http://cnnchile.com/noticia/2013/11/01/este-es-el-line-up-definitivo-de-lollapalooza-chile-2014-encabezado-por-arcade-fire-y-red-hot-chili-peppers|archivedate=2 November 2013|date=1 November 2013|title=Esta pasando. Lo estas viendo|publisher=CNN|language=es}}</ref> Argentina,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11227561|title=Lorde joins Lollapalooza line-up|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> Brazil<ref>{{cite web|first=Reggie|last=Ugwu|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/festivals/6041368/lollapalooza-brazil-2014-phoenix-arcade-fire-lorde-rock-sao-paulo|title=Lollapalooza Brazil 2014: Phoenix, Arcade Fire, Lorde Rock S\u00e3o Paulo|date=8 April 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\u2014and the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella Festival]] in California.<ref>{{cite news|first=Reggie|last=Ugwu|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/coachella-2014-lorde-makes-desert-695863|title=Coachella 2014: Lorde Makes Desert Debut|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=14 April 2014|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> She subsequently embarked on an [[Pure Heroine Tour|international concert tour]], commencing in North America in early 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5839820/lorde-announces-north-american-tour-dates|title=Lorde Announces North American Tour Dates|date=16 December 2013|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|accessdate=9 September 2014|work=Billboard}}</ref> Amidst her solo activities, Lorde joined the surviving members of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] to perform \"[[All Apologies]]\" during the band's induction ceremony at the [[Rock N' Roll Hall of Fame]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6049353/nirvana-joined-by-joan-jett-kim-gordon-st-vincent-lorde-at-rock-hall-ceremony|title=Nirvana Joined By Joan Jett, Kim Gordon, St. Vincent, Lorde at Rock Hall Ceremony|date=11 April 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=9 May 2014}}</ref> Band members [[Krist Novoselic]] and [[Dave Grohl]] explained that they selected Lorde because her songs represented \"Nirvana aesthetics\" for their perceptive lyrics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/04/dave-grohl-on-lorde-she-represents-the-nirvana-aesthetic-amid-all-that-stripper-pop/|title=Dave Grohl on Lorde: she represents the 'Nirvana aesthetic' amid 'all that stripper pop'|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=26 April 2014|first=Chris|last=Coplan|accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> Lorde also curated the accompanying [[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1 (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1]]'' (2014), overseeing the collation of the album's content as well as recording four tracks, including its lead single \"[[Yellow Flicker Beat]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/6289238/lorde-hunger-games-soundtrack-kanye-west|title=Lorde's 'Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Pt. 1' Soundtrack to Feature Kanye West, Chvrches, Charli XCX|first=Zach|last=Dionne|work=Billboard|date=21 October 2014|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> In 2015, the track earned Lorde a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref name=\"2015GoldenGlobes\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Joe|title=2015 Golden Globe Nominees: Lorde, Lana Del Rey, Trent Reznor & More|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6405535/2015-golden-globe-nominees-lorde-lana-del-rey-trent-reznor|accessdate=13 December 2014|work=Billboard|date=11 December 2014}}</ref> Later that year, she was featured on British electronic duo [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]]'s song \"[[Magnets (song)|Magnets]]\" off their album ''[[Caracal (album)|Caracal]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/sep/27/disclosure-caracal-review-dance-duo-lorde-miguel-sam-smith|title=Disclosure: Caracal review \u2013 dance duo's second is saved by the guests|first=Michael|last=Cragg|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Melodrama''===\n[[File:Lorde Brisbane Nov 2017 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|alt=Lorde playing a sampler onstage wearing a pink dress with bedazzled jewels and a flower crown on her head.|Lorde performing in November 2017]]\nAt the [[2016 Brit Awards]] in February, Lorde and [[David Bowie]]'s final touring band gave a tribute performance of his 1971 song \"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/feb/25/david-bowie-brits-tribute-lorde-duncan-jones|title=David Bowie's son thanks Brits for 'beautiful' tribute by Lorde|work=The Guardian|date=25 February 2016|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> Pianist [[Mike Garson]], a frequent band member for Bowie, explained that Bowie's family and management selected Lorde because he admired her and felt she was \"the future of music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/mar/22/david-bowie-lorde-future-of-music|title=David Bowie saw Lorde as 'the future of music'|work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2016|accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref> Later that year, Lorde co-wrote \"[[Heartlines]]\", a song by New Zealand music duo [[Broods]] from their album ''[[Conscious (Broods album)|Conscious]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7401141/lorde-broods-heartlines-co-wrote|title=Lorde Returns! Hear 'Heartlines,' the Song She Co-Wrote With Broods|first=Joe|last=Lynch|work=Billboard|date=10 June 2016|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe lead single from her second studio album ''[[Melodrama (Lorde album)|Melodrama]]'', \"[[Green Light (Lorde song)|Green Light]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39143565|title=All you need to know about Lorde's new single, Green Light|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017|author=Savage, Mark}}</ref> was released in March 2017 to widespread acclaim; several publications ranked it as one of the best songs of the year, ''[[NME Single of the Year|NME]]'' and ''The Guardian'' placing it in the top spot on their respective lists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/22/pazz-jop-the-top-albums-and-singles-of-2017/|title=Pazz & Jop: It's Kendrick's and Cardi's World. We're All Just Living in It|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=22 January 2018|accessdate=10 February 2018}}<br />\n{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/nmes-best-tracks-year-2017-2161431/5/|title=Best Songs of the Year 2017|date=27 November 2017|work=[[NME]]|access-date=4 December 2017}}<br />\n{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/04/the-top-100-tracks-of-2017|title=The top 100 tracks of 2017|work=The Guardian|date=4 December 2017|first=Ben|last=Beaumont-Thomas|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref> It achieved moderate commercial success, reaching number one in New Zealand, number four in Australia and number nine in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Lorde&titel=Green+Light&cat=s|title=Lorde \u2013 Green Light|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=20 February 2019}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Lorde/chart-history/canadian-hot-100/song/1016733|title=Lorde \u2013 Green Light Chart History \u2013 Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> Later that month, she co-wrote and provided background vocals for American indie pop band [[Bleachers (band)|Bleachers]]'s song \"[[Don't Take the Money]]\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Geslani |first1=Michelle |title=Bleachers and Lorde link up on new song 'Don't Take the Money' \u2014 listen |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/bleachers-and-lorde-link-up-on-new-song-dont-take-the-money-listen/ |accessdate=29 December 2018 |work=Consequence of Sound |date=31 March 2017}}</ref> taken from their album ''[[Gone Now]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Jack Antonoff Details Bleachers' 'Gone Now' LP |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/jack-antonoff-details-bleachers-gone-now-lp-107182/ |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Rolling Stone |date=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn ''Melodrama'', Lorde attempted to showcase her maturity as a songwriter and incorporated her post-breakup introspection.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629174023/http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/music/a9766/lords-new-album-different/|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/music/a9766/lords-new-album-different/|title=Why Lorde's Next Album Will Be 'Totally Different'|first=Lauren|last=Valenti|work=[[Marie Claire]]|date=5 June 2014|archivedate=29 June 2016}}</ref> The album was released in June 2017 and received widespread acclaim; [[Metacritic]] placed it second on their list of the best-received records of 2017 based on inclusions in publications' year-end lists, behind [[Kendrick Lamar]]'s ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|Damn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-10-best-albums-of-2017|title=Best of 2017: Music Critic Top 10 Lists|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> It reached number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], earning Lorde her first number one on the chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7842114/lorde-melodrama-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|title=Lorde Earns First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Melodrama'|work=Billboard|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=25 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626022349/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7842114/lorde-melodrama-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|archivedate=26 June 2017}}</ref> and on album charts of Australia, Canada and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Lorde/chart-history/canadian-albums|title=Lorde Chart History \u2013 Canadian Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=21 January 2019}}<br />\n{{cite web |title=Charts.org.nz \u2013 Lorde \u2013 Melodrama |url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Lorde&titel=Melodrama&cat=a |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> It earned a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards|60th ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/8096810/grammys-2018-bruno-mars-album-of-the-year|title=Bruno Mars Completes His Big Night by Winning Album of the Year for '24K Magic' at the 2018 Grammy Awards|work=Billboard|last=Lamarre|first=Carl|date=28 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319062911/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/8096810/grammys-2018-bruno-mars-album-of-the-year|archivedate=19 March 2018}}</ref> Two other singles from the album were released: \"[[Perfect Places]]\" and a remix of \"[[Homemade Dynamite]]\" featuring [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]], [[Post Malone]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lorde-announces-new-sza-featuring-homemade-dynamite-remix/|title=Lorde Announces New SZA-Featuring \"Homemade Dynamite\" Remix|last=Kim|first=Michelle|date=|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nTo promote ''Melodrama'', Lorde embarked on an [[Melodrama World Tour|international concert tour]], the first leg of which took place in Europe in late 2017, featuring Khalid as the supporting act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/06/lorde-announces-melodrama-world-tour.html|title=Lorde Announces Melodrama World Tour, New Song Due Out at Midnight|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=8 June 2017|first=Natalia|last=Barr |accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> She later announced the North American leg, held in March 2018, with [[Run the Jewels]], [[Mitski]] and [[Tove Styrke]] as opening acts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stubblebine |first1=Allison |title=Lorde Reveals Run the Jewels, Mitski & Tove Styrke as Support for Melodrama Tour in North America |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7988877/lorde-melodrama-tour-support-run-the-jewels-mitski-tove-styrke-north-america-dates |accessdate=30 May 2018 |work=Billboard |date=4 October 2017}}</ref> A [[Melodrama World Tour#Israel controversy|political controversy]] occurred in December 2017 when Lorde cancelled her scheduled June 2018 concert in Israel following an online campaign by Palestinian solidarity activists supporting the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] (BDS) campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beaumont|first1=Peter|title=Lorde cancels Israel concert after pro-Palestinian campaign|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/25/lorde-cancels-israel-concert-after-pro-palestinian-campaign|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=The Guardian|date=25 December 2017}}</ref> While Lorde did not explicitly indicate her reasons for cancelling, she admitted that she had been unaware of the political turmoil there and \"the right decision at this time is to cancel\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lorde-cancels-tel-aviv-concert-after-calls-to-boycott-israel-199358/|title=Lorde Cancels Tel Aviv Concert After Calls to Boycott Israel|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|date=24 December 2017|work=Rolling Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827210017/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lorde-cancels-tel-aviv-concert-after-calls-to-boycott-israel-199358/|archivedate=27 August 2018}}</ref> Pro-Palestine groups welcomed her decision,<ref>{{cite news|title=Lorde's artistic right to cancel gig in Tel Aviv|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/05/lordes-artistic-right-to-cancel-gig-in-tel-aviv|accessdate=10 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> while pro-Israel groups were critical of the cancellation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lorde called a bigot over cancelled Israel concert in full-page Washington Post ad|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/01/lorde-called-a-bigot-over-israel-stance-in-full-page-washington-post-ad|accessdate=1 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2018}}</ref> ''Billboard'' included Lorde on their 2017 edition of 21 Under 21.<ref>{{cite news |title=21 Under 21 2017: Music's Next Generation |url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/7980786/21-under-21-shawn-mendes-lorde-khalid-camila |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=28 September 2017}}</ref> In November 2018, Lorde became a patron of MusicHelps (formerly the New Zealand Music Foundation), a musical charity helping New Zealanders who are vulnerable to or experiencing serious health issues.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lorde becomes patron of MusicHelps, a musical charity helping Kiwis in need |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2018/11/lorde-becomes-patron-of-musichelps-a-musical-charity-helping-kiwis-in-need.html |accessdate=23 May 2019 | publisher=[[Newshub]] |date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Influences===\n{{multiple image\n| footer = Lorde's influences include [[David Bowie]] (left) and [[Robyn]] (right).<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\"/>\n| image1 = David Bowie - Zagreb.jpg\n| alt1   = An image of a man performing onstage with an acoustic guitar, wearing a white dress shirt and a black suit vest.\n| width1 = 143\n| image2 = RobynIn2011 cropped.jpg\n| alt    = A close-up image of a woman smiling away from the camera wearing a white bomber jacket and a black blouse.\n| width2 = 160\n| align = right\n}}\nLorde grew up listening to American [[jazz]] and [[soul music|soul]] musicians [[Billie Holiday]], [[Sam Cooke]], [[Etta James]], and [[Otis Redding]], whose music she admires for \"harvesting their suffering.\"<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\"/> She also listened to her parents' favourite records by the likes of [[Cat Stevens]], [[Neil Young]], and [[Fleetwood Mac]] in her early years.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> During production of ''Pure Heroine'', Lorde cited influences from [[electronic music]] producers, including [[SBTRKT]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]],<ref name=\"James\">{{cite news|title=Lorde&nbsp;\u2013 New Music|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/new-music/10296479/Lorde-New-Music.html|accessdate=14 September 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=11 September 2013|first=James|last=Lachno}}</ref> and [[Sleigh Bells (band)|Sleigh Bells]],<ref>{{cite interview|subject=Lorde|interviewer=[[Lisa Kennedy Montgomery]]|title=Lorde In-Studio with Kennedy|date=20 August 2013|publisher=KYSR|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e2y6H3MCqsk|at=2:58}}</ref> impressed by \"their vocals in a really interesting way, whether it might be chopping up a vocal part or really lash or layering a vocal.\"<ref name=\"lordevmusic\">{{cite web|first=Pip|last=Cowley|url=http://www.vmusic.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/interviews/lorde-q-a|title=Lorde Q&A|publisher=V Music Australia|accessdate=16 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408133117/http://www.vmusic.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/interviews/lorde-q-a|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpostroyals\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/24/lorde-interview_n_3644831.html|title=Lorde, 16-Year-Old New Zealand Musician, Talks 'Royals' Video, Feminism And More|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=30 January 2014|first=Noah|last=Michelson}}</ref> Lorde also stated that she was inspired by the initially hidden identities of [[Burial (musician)|Burial]] and [[The Weeknd]], explaining, \"I feel like mystery is more interesting.\"<ref name=\"CoverStory\"/> Other inspirations include [[Grace Jones]],<ref name=\"Lorde\">{{cite web|author=Julie Naughton and Pete Born|title=Lorde on Influences&nbsp;\u2013 and Cosmetics|date=20 May 2014|work=Women's Wear Daily|url=http://wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/people/lorde-on-influences-and-cosmetics-7688319/|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]], [[Yeasayer]], [[Animal Collective]], [[Bon Iver]],<ref name=\"TeenVogue\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/entertainment/music/2013-07/lorde-interview|title=Get to Know Lorde, the 16-Year-Old Pop Star Everyone's Talking About|first=Casey|last=Lewis|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> [[The Smiths]],<ref name=\"huffpostroyals\"/> [[Arcade Fire]],<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\"/> [[Laurie Anderson]],<ref name=\"Weiner\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lordes-teenage-dream-20131028|title=Lorde: The Rise of Pop's Edgiest Teen|first=Jonah|last=Weiner|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=28 October 2013|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> [[Kanye West]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]],<ref name=DigitalSpycoUKintimidatingPeers>{{cite web|url=http://DigitalSpy.co.UK/music/news/a529048/lorde-i-relate-to-kanye-west-and-i-feel-intimidated-by-teenage-girls.html|title=Lorde 'I relate to Kanye West and I feel intimidated by teenage girls'|date=5 November 2013|last=Simpson|first=Leah|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref> and David Bowie.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/lorde-reveals-david-bowie-inspiration-second-album-new-single/|title=Lorde reveals David Bowie was inspiration for second album as new single Green Light released|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=21 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nLyrically, Lorde cited her mother, a poet, as the primary influence for her songwriting.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> She also named several authors, including [[Kurt Vonnegut]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boardman |first1=Madeline |title=Lorde On Her Inspirations, Style, And Rise To Fame |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/16/lorde-inspirations-style-rise-to-fame_n_4611442.html |website=HuffPost |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126172712/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/16/lorde-inspirations-style-rise-to-fame_n_4611442.html|archivedate=26 November 2014 |date=16 January 2014}}</ref> [[Raymond Carver]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\">{{cite web|last=Selby|first=Jenn|url=https://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/article/lorde-royals-pure-heroine-interview-music-videos|title=Lorde Royals Pure Heroine Interview|work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|date=28 October 2013|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> [[Wells Tower]],<ref name=\"iheartradionz\">{{cite interview|subject=Lorde|interviewer=[[Polly Gillespie]]|title=ZMTV&nbsp;\u2013 Lorde Interview (Polly Speaks to Lorde Before The iHeartRadio NZ Launch)|date=18 September 2013|publisher=ZM|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cir4TKJlupA|at=2:18}}</ref> [[Tobias Wolff]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\"/> [[Claire Vaye Watkins]],<ref name=\"iheartradionz\"/> [[Sylvia Plath]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\"/> [[Walt Whitman]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\"/> and [[T. S. Eliot]] as lyrical inspirations, particularly noting their [[sentence structure]]s.<ref name=\"James\"/> When writing her second album, ''Melodrama'', Lorde took inspiration from the melodic styles of a variety of musicians, including [[Phil Collins]],<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\"/> [[Don Henley]],<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/12/magazine/the-return-of-lorde.html|title=The Return of Lorde|first=Jonah|last=Weiner|date=12 April 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> [[Tom Petty]],<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\">{{cite web|last1=Mackay |first1=Emily |title=Lorde talks fame, growing up and her new album 'Melodrama' \u2013 NME |url=http://www.nme.com/features/lorde-interview-2017-melodrama-nme-2088564 |website=NME |accessdate=19 June 2017 |date=16 June 2017}}</ref> [[Joni Mitchell]],<ref name=\"TheGuardianProfile\"/> [[Leonard Cohen]],<ref name=\"TheGuardianProfile\">{{cite news|last1=Lamont|first1=Tom|title=Lorde: 'I want to be Leonard Cohen. I want to be Joni Mitchell'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/17/lorde-singer-songwriter-music-royals-tom-lamont|accessdate=23 February 2018|work=The Guardian|date=17 June 2017}}</ref> and [[Robyn]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Lorde Uses Robyn's 'Dancing On My Own' as Studio Inspiration|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6560649/lorde-robyn-dancing-on-my-own-studio-next-album|accessdate=23 February 2018|work=Billboard|date=7 May 2015}}</ref> During the recording process, Lorde stated that [[Frank Ocean]]'s 2016 album ''[[Blonde (Frank Ocean album)|Blonde]]'' inspired her to eschew \"traditional song structures.\"<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\"/> She frequently listened to [[Paul Simon]]'s 1986 album ''[[Graceland (Paul Simon album)|Graceland]]'' while riding subways in [[New York City]] and on taxi rides on the way home from parties in her hometown of Auckland.<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\">{{cite news|last1=Shaffer|first1=Claire|title=The Influences on Lorde's 'Melodrama': Frank Ocean, Robyn, Bowie and 10 Other Artists Who Shaped Its Sound|url=http://www.newsweek.com/lorde-melodrama-influences-frank-ocean-robyn-bowie-prince-628768|accessdate=23 February 2018|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=24 June 2017}}</ref> She cited the science fiction short story \"[[There Will Come Soft Rains (short story)|There Will Come Soft Rains]]\" (1950) by [[Ray Bradbury]] as inspiration for much of ''Melodrama''{{'s}} story, relating it to her own realities she faced.<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/>\n\n===Musical style and songwriting===\n{{Listen\n| filename = Royals Lorde.ogg\n| title = \"Royals\" (2013)\n| description = Lorde's debut studio album ''Pure Heroine'' was noted for its minimalist production, exemplified by the [[art pop]] and [[electropop]] single \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\".<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/12/best-songs-2013/131125-best-songs-lorde/|title=50 Best Songs of 2013: No. 15&nbsp;\u2013 Lorde: 'Royals'|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR\"/><ref name=\"PureHeroineConsequence\"/>\n| format = [[Ogg]]\n| pos = right\n}}\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in 2017, Lorde declared \"I don\u2019t think about staying in my genre lane\".<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] characterised her style as primarily [[electropop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lorde-mn0003085111/biography|title=Lorde Biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|first=Stephen|last=Thomas Erlewine|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> Upon the release of ''Pure Heroine'', contemporary critics described her music as electropop,<ref name=\"PureHeroineConsequence\"/> [[art pop]],<ref name=\"GlobeAndMail\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/album-reviews/in-an-age-of-manufactured-stars-lorde-is-a-refreshing-change/article14678181/|title=In an age of manufactured stars, Lorde is a refreshing change|first=Brad|last=Wheeler|date=7 October 2013|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> [[dream pop]],<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/175719-lorde-pure-heroine-2495719039.html|title=Lorde: Pure Heroine|first=Evan|last=Sawdey|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=10 October 2013|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> [[indie pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/artists/31696-lorde/|title=Lorde|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=4 February 2019|quote=Melodrama [...] told the story of a single party, and advanced her indie-pop sound into synesthetic revelry}}</ref> and [[indie-electro]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mahoney|first=Stan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/09/lorde-review-voice-of-the-generation-with-a-dash-of-gold-lame-and-confetti|title=Lorde review&nbsp;\u2013 voice of the generation, with a dash of gold lam\u00e9 and confetti|work=The Guardian|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> Critics also noted the influence of [[hip hop music|hip hop]] on the album's song structures,<ref name=\"PH_reviews\">{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17931/reviews/4147053|title=Album Review: Lorde \u2013 Pure Heroine|work=[[Drowned in Sound]]|first=Sammy|last=Maine|date=28 October 2013|accessdate=1 February 2019}}<br />{{cite web |last=Interrante |first=Scott |title=Gold Teeth, White Teeth, and Lorde's 'Pure Heroine' |url=https://www.popmatters.com/175777-gold-teeth-white-teeth-and-lordes-pure-heroine-2495718477.html |accessdate=4 June 2018 |work=PopMatters |date=17 October 2013}}</ref> as well as its unconventional pop sound and minimalist production.<ref name=\"NPR\"/> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' pointed that the minimal production of ''Pure Heroine'' \"allows [her] to sing any melody she wants, layering them over one another to create a [[chorus effect|choral effect]]\".<ref name=\"PureHeroineConsequence\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2013/09/album-review-lorde-pure-heroine/|title=Lorde&nbsp;\u2013 Pure Heroine {{!}} Album Review|work=Consequence of Sound|date=30 September 2013|first=Jon|last=Hadusek|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> ''Melodrama'' was a departure from the hip hop-oriented minimalist style of its predecessor, incorporating [[piano]] instrumentation and [[maximalism#music|maximalist]] electronic beats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/album-review-lorde-melodrama/|title=Lorde \u2013 Melodrama|work=Consequence of Sound|last=Weiss|first=Dan|date=19 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105011419/https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/album-review-lorde-melodrama/|archivedate=5 January 2018}}<br />{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/18/lorde-melodrama-review-maximum-overwrought-green-light-liability|title=Lorde: Melodrama review \u2013 maximum overwrought|last=Empire|first=Kitty|date=18 June 2017|work=The Guardian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223014704/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/18/lorde-melodrama-review-maximum-overwrought-green-light-liability|archivedate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nLorde utilises her vocals and does not play musical instruments on her records or onstage, elaborating, \"[My] voice needs to have the focus. My vocal-scape is really important\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/21/arts/music/mutual-admiration-across-the-sea-across-the-years.html|title=Mutual Admiration, Across the Sea, Across the Years|first=Melena|last=Ryzik|date=20 May 2014|work=The New York Times|accessdate=16 June 2014}}<br />{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/meet-lorde-shes-a-talented-teenage-badass|title=Meet Lorde: She's a Talented Teenage Badass|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|first=Liza|last=Darwin|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' described Lorde's vocals as \"unique and powerfully intriguing\",<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> while ''Billboard'' characterised her voice as \"dynamic, smoky and restrained\".<ref name=\"BillboardTrackByTrack\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5733177/lorde-pure-heroine-track-by-track-review|title=Lorde, 'Pure Heroine' Track-By-Track Review|date=25 September 2013|work=Billboard|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' wrote that Lorde's voice \"is the alpha and omega of her talent\", characterising it as \"mystifying and alluring\" that harmonised well with the electronic production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/lorde-ipure-heroinei-103883|title=Lorde: Pure Heroine \u2013 Music Review|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|first=Kevin|last=McFarland|date=8 October 2013|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' noted that her songs incorporated the [[mixolydian mode]], a melodic structure used in \"[[blues]]-based and [[alternative rock]]\" music, which set her songs apart from those in pop music for not fitting a common [[major chord|major]] or [[minor chord|minor]] chord.<ref>{{cite news|last=Witmer|first=Phil|title=Here's the Music Theory Behind Why Lorde's Songwriting Is Objectively Kickass|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/wnk57n/heres-why-lordes-songwriting-is-objectively-kickass|accessdate=5 January 2018|work=Vice|date=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nRegarding her songwriting process, Lorde explained that the foundation to her songs began with the lyrics, which could sometimes stem from a singular word meant to summarise a specific idea she had tried to identify.<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\"/> For \"Tennis Court\", Lorde wrote the music before lyrics.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Lorde|year=2013|title=Lyrical Influences (VEVO LIFT): Brought to You By McDonald's|medium=video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zCSFHsd7NWA|accessdate=22 November 2013|publisher=VEVO/YouTube|time=1:49|quote=I think my writing process with 'Tennis Court' was quite different to how I normally write. Generally, I will have a lyric forming before I go into the studio. But with this one, we wrote the music and beat before we wrote anything lyrically}}</ref> She stated that the songwriting on ''Pure Heroine'' developed from the perspective of an observer.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/> Similarly, in an interview with ''NME'', Lorde acknowledged that she used words of inclusion (such as \"we\" and \"us\") throughout her debut album, while her follow-up ''Melodrama'' presented a shift to [[first-person narrative]], employing more introspective lyrics inspired by Lorde's personal struggles post-breakup and viewpoints on post-teenage maturity.<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/> Lorde's neurological condition [[chromesthesia]] influenced her songwriting on the album; it led her to arrange colours according to each song's theme and emotion.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/>\n\n==Public image==\n[[File:Lorde - Coachella 2014 (07).jpg|thumb|upright|Lorde is known for her unchoreographed dancing onstage, which has polarised audiences.|alt=Lorde performing onstage with spontaneous and unchoreographed moves, wearing a blazer and white sneakers]]\nLorde's stage name bears her fascination with \"[[royal family|royals]] and [[aristocracy (class)|aristocracy]]\"; she added an \"e\" after the name Lord, which she felt was too masculine, to make it more feminine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/08/lorde-101-who-is-this-16-year-old-singer.html|title=Lorde 101: Who Is This 16-Year-Old New Zealand Singer Everyone's Talking About?|first=Lindsey|last=Weber|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=19 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821231605/https://www.vulture.com/2013/08/lorde-101-who-is-this-16-year-old-singer.html|archivedate=21 August 2013|access-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She described her public image as something that \"naturally\" came to her and was identical to her real life personality.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=Harvey|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/9561880/Lorde-keeps-it-real-about-sex-appeal|title=Lorde keeps it real about sex appeal|website=Stuff.co.nz|date=29 December 2013|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> Lorde is a self-identified [[Feminism|feminist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11151243|title=Lorde says sex on stage the next step for pop stars|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=4 November 2013|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref> ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' opined that her feminist ideology was different from her contemporaries due to Lorde's disinterest in sexualised performances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11194512|title=Lorde makes feminism a class issue|first=Rosemary|last=Overell|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=31 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131193902/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11194512|archivedate=31 January 2014|access-date=6 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The singer proclaimed herself in an interview with ''[[V (American magazine)|V]]'' as a \"hugely [[sex-positive movement|sex-positive]] person\", saying, \"I have nothing against anyone getting naked.&nbsp;... I just don't think it really would complement my music in any way or help me tell a story any better\".<ref name=\"varietyinterview\">{{cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/praise-the-lorde/|title=Praise the Lorde|work=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|first=William|last=Defebaugh|date=16 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009092638/https://vmagazine.com/article/praise-the-lorde/|archivedate=9 October 2018|access-date=9 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCritical reception of Lorde is generally positive, praise concentrated on her maturity both musically and lyrically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/lorde-review-star-shines-under-the-burden-of-expectation-20171122-gzq9gc.html|title=Lorde review: Star shines under the burden of expectation|first=George|last=Palathingal|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=22 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203043309/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/lorde-review-star-shines-under-the-burden-of-expectation-20171122-gzq9gc.html|archivedate=3 February 2019|access-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' called her \"the pop prodigy\" who was not conformed to boundaries and always sought experimentation.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/> ''Billboard'' recognised Lorde as a spokesperson for a \"female rock resurgence\" by introducing her works to rock and alternative radio, which had seen a traditional male dominance.<ref name=\"billboardalternative\">{{cite news |last=Trust |first=Gary |title=Lorde, HAIM Bring Girl Power To Alternative |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5755301/lorde-haim-bring-girl-power-to-alternative |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Billboard |date=11 October 2013}}</ref> The publication also named her the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|New Queen of Alternative]]\" in a 2013 cover story.<ref name=\"CoverStory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5687161/lorde-the-billboard-cover-story|title=Lorde: The Billboard Cover Story|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|date=6 September 2013|accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref> Journalist [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic towards Lorde's styles, labelling the singer as \"a pop property\" that was indistinguishable from other mainstream artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Lorde|title=Lorde|first=Robert|last=Christgau|authorlink=Robert Christgau|publisher=Robert Christgau Consumer Guide|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703050859/https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Lorde|archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nLorde's critiques of mainstream culture on ''Pure Heroine'' earned her the title \"the voice of [[Millennials|her generation]]\",<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> a label she dismissed, saying that \"young people have never needed a specialised spokesperson\".<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/> [[Jon Caramanica]], writing for ''The New York Times'', credited Lorde for bringing forth a \"wave of female rebellion\" to mainstream audiences that embraced an \"anti-pop\" sentiment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/arts/music/in-lordes-wake-a-groundswell-of-female-rebels-in-pop.html|title=In Lorde's Wake, a Groundswell of Female Rebels in Pop|first=Jon|last= Caramanica|date=30 August 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> Sharing a similar viewpoint, an [[op-ed]] of ''Vice'' recognised the singer as the reformer for the teenage pop scene, shifting from [[Britney Spears]]'s renowned [[bubblegum pop]] to modern-day \"mainstream melancholy\" and \"millennial darkness\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/rdz7ay/britney-vs-lorde-a-case-study|title=The Shifting Image of the Teenage Female Pop Star: How We Got from Britney Spears to Lorde|work=Vice|first=Aliza |last=Abarbanel|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' and [[NPR]] credited her debut studio album ''Pure Heroine'' as the foundation of that transformation.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/08/31/638897130/lorde-is-the-21st-centurys-author-of-adolescent-evolution|title=Lorde Is The 21st Century's Author Of Adolescent Evolution|first=Cyrena|last=Tourous|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=21 January 2018}}<br />{{cite web|last=Morris |first=Alex |title=Lorde's Growing Pains: How Pop's Favorite Outsider Wrote Her Next Chapter |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lordes-growing-pains-how-pops-favorite-outsider-wrote-her-next-chapter-127944/ |accessdate=14 December 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |date=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer onstage persona, particularly her signature unchoreographed dancing, has polarised audiences. Her detractors have described her dance moves as \"awkward\" in comparison to contemporary stage performers.<ref>\n{{cite web|last1=Newshub Staff|title=Lorde hits back at critics of her SNL dance|url=http://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2017/03/lorde-hits-back-at-critics-of-her-snl-dance.html|accessdate=8 February 2018|publisher=Newshub|date=14 March 2017}}<br />\n{{cite web|last1=Rosen|first1=Christopher|title=Lorde defends controversial VMAs performance|url=http://ew.com/music/2017/09/10/lorde-defends-vmas/|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=10 September 2017}}<br />\n{{cite news|last1=Meltzer|first1=Marisa|title=For a Power Girl, Cheers and Disses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/fashion/Lorde-Ella-Yelich-OConnor-Grammy.html|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=The New York Times|date=7 February 2014}}<br />\n{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/76GoMheqj?url=http://time.com/4700910/lorde-on-snl-dancing-criticism/|url=http://time.com/4700910/lorde-on-snl-dancing-criticism/|title=Lorde Hits Back at Criticism of Her Saturday Night Live Dancing|first=Megan|last=McCluskey|work=Time|date=14 March 2017|archivedate=18 February 2019|access-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}\n</ref> ''[[The Fader]]'' expressed that she should be celebrated for her dancing as it is \"more freeform and spontaneous\" than structured choreography and \"speaks an entirely different expressive language\". The publication further elaborated that her \"stage presence [is] more impactful than the average pop performance\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cliff|first1=Aimee|title=Why Lorde Is A Great Dancer|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/25/lorde-dancing-green-light-snl-coachella|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=[[The Fader]]|date=25 April 2017}}</ref> Lorde's works have directly influenced several contemporary artists, including [[Amanda Palmer]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Axeman |first1=Stephen |title=Amanda Palmer on \u201cThere Will Be No Intermission\u201d |url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/interviews/amanda_palmer_on_there_will_be_no_intermission/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Under the Radar |date=6 May 2019}}</ref> [[Amandla Stenberg]],<ref name=\"rsinfluence\">{{cite news |last1=Spanos |first1=Brittany |title=18 Teens Shaking Up Pop Culture |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/18-teens-shaking-up-pop-culture-11682/amandla-stenberg-16-228496/ |accessdate=27 May 2019 |work=Rolling Stone |date=16 September 2015}}</ref> [[Charly Bliss]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Jonathan |title=How Charly Bliss Learned to Love Pop |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/charly-bliss-young-enough-interview-835213/ |accessdate=19 May 2019 |work=Rolling Stone |date=17 May 2019}}</ref> [[Conan Gray]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Caitlin |title=Conan Gray Writes Intimate, Practically Perfect Pop Songs Inspired By Lorde, Taylor Swift, And Adele |url=https://uproxx.com/pop/conan-gray-primer/ |accessdate=7 September 2019 |work=Uproxx |date=4 September 2019}}</ref> [[Courtney Love]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Trendell |first1=Andrew |title=Courtney Love on her new album: 'It'll have beats. Like Lorde has beats' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/courtney-love-discusses-autobiography-new-album-inspired-lorde-lana-del-rey-2068589 |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=NME |date=9 May 2017}}</ref> [[Fletcher (singer)|Fletcher]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Selzer |first1=Jillian |title=Fletcher Debuts New Power Ballad \"Wasted Youth,\" Interview |url=https://vmagazine.com/article/premiere-fletcher-debuts-new-power-ballad-wasted-youth/ |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=V |date=26 August 2016}}</ref> [[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Weatherby |first=Taylor |title=James Bay Explains How Lorde, Frank Ocean & David Bowie Played Into His 'Evolving' Sound For New Single 'Wild Love' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8098843/james-bay-wild-love-interview-new-song |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Billboard |date=8 February 2018}}</ref> Khalid,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Holden |first1=Steve |title=Why Khalid loves Fleetwood Mac and Sir Elton John |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/41610461/why-khalid-loves-fleetwood-mac-and-sir-elton-john |accessdate=14 December 2018 |publisher=BBC |date=13 October 2017}}</ref> [[K.Flay]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Takeover Tuesday Playlist: K.Flay Picks Her Favorite Lyrics From Lorde, Cage the Elephant & More |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8523498/kflay-playlist-takeover-tuesday |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Billboard |date=23 July 2019}}</ref> [[Nina Nesbitt]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Sabrina |title=Nina Nesbitt Talks New Single, Songwriting and Being a DIY Female Producer: Interview |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7865864/nina-nesbitt-the-moments-im-missing-songwriting-diy-female-producer |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Billboard |date=14 July 2017}}</ref> [[Sigrid (singer)|Sigrid]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Longo |first1=Joseph |title=Don't Kill Sigrid's Vibe: Scandinavia's Breakout Pop Sensation on Her Debut Album 'Sucker Punch' |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/dont-kill-sigrids-vibe-scandinavias-breakout-pop-sensation-on-her-debut-album-sucker-punch |accessdate=30 September 2019 |work=The Daily Beast |date=9 March 2019}}</ref> [[Tavi Gevinson]],<ref name=\"rsinfluence\"/> [[Tessa Violet]],<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |title=Why We're Infatuated with Tessa Violet |url=https://thefullest.com/2018/08/07/why-were-infatuated-with-tessa-violet/ |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=The Fullest |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> [[The Aces (indie pop band)|The Aces]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cirisano |first1=Tatiana |title=Chartbreaker: Pop-Rock Quartet The Aces Were Inspired By Lorde To Get Serious |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070475/the-aces-stuck-interview-chartbreaker |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=Billboard |date=15 December 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Tove Lo]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tanzer |first1=Miles |title=How Tove Lo got really weird and made the best album of her career |url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/12/05/tove-lo-blue-lips-interview-disco-tits |accessdate=14 December 2018 |work=The Fader |date=5 December 2017}}</ref> [[Troye Sivan]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeRosa |first1=Nicole |title=Q&A with Troye Sivan |url=https://music.allaccess.com/qa-with-troye-sivan/ |accessdate=26 May 2019 |publisher=AllAccess.com |date=22 April 2016}}</ref> and [[Yungblud]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scrudato |first1=Ken |title=BlackBook Interview with Brit Rocker Yungblud and His Guide to Authentic, Indie London |url=https://bbook.com/nightlife/interview-w-brit-rocker-yungblud-guide-authentic-indie-london/ |accessdate=6 October 2019 |work=BlackBook |publisher=Vibe |date=9 February 2018}}</ref> She placed at number 12 on NPR's 2018 readers poll of the most influential female musicians of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lorusso |first=Marissa |title=Turning the Tables: Your List Of The 21st Century's Most Influential Women Musicians |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/20/668372321/turning-the-tables-your-list-of-the-21st-centurys-most-influential-women-musicia |accessdate=14 December 2018 |publisher=NPR |date=20 November 2018}}</ref> Lorde was parodied in the ''[[South Park]]'' episodes \"[[The Cissy]]\" and \"[[Rehash (South Park)|Rehash]]\", broadcast in October and December 2014, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6281319/lorde-south-park-spin-cissy|title=Watch Lorde Return to 'South Park' & See Her Reaction|work=Billboard|first=Chris|last=Payne|date=9 October 2014|accessdate=3 February 2019}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/12/south-park-mocks-music-industry-with-lorde-and-tupac-holograms-watch/|title=South Park mocks music industry with Lorde and Tupac holograms \u2013 watch|date=4 December 2014|work=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=3 February 2019|first=Alex|\nlast=Young}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom late 2013 to early 2016, Lorde was in a relationship with New Zealand photographer James Lowe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roxborough|first=Scott|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6028981/lordes-boyfriend-on-singers-accomplishments-i-couldnt-be-prouder|title=Lorde's Boyfriend on Singer's accomplishments: 'I Couldn't Be Prouder'|date=27 March 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=9 September 2014}}<br>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/celebrities/75984352/Reports-Lorde-has-split-from-her-boyfriend-James-Lowe-after-three-years|title=Reports: Lorde has split from her boyfriend James Lowe after three years|date=19 January 2016|accessdate=14 March 2018|website=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref> In January 2016, she relocated from Devonport to [[Herne Bay, New Zealand|Herne Bay]], an affluent suburb in Auckland, where she purchased a NZ$2.84 (USD$2.01) million home.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11574655|title=Lorde pays $2.84m for her city villa|date=16 January 2016|newspaper=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> She holds both New Zealand and Croatian citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedubrovniktimes.com/news/croatia/item/3053-lorde-reveals-that-she-has-croatian-citizenship|title=Lorde reveals that she has Croatian citizenship|last=Thomas|first=Mark|date=8 September 2017|work=The Dubrovnik Times|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Lorde}}\nAfter her breakthrough, Lorde won four [[New Zealand Music Awards]] at the [[2013 New Zealand Music Awards|2013 ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lorde wins big at 2013 NZ Music Awards|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Lorde-wins-big-at-2013-NZ-Music-Awards/tabid/418/articleID/322318/Default.aspx|accessdate=21 November 2013|work=3 News|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> The single \"Royals\" earned the [[APRA Awards (New Zealand)|APRA Silver Scroll Award]], and two Grammy Awards for Best Pop Solo Performance and Song of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Lydia|title=Lorde's Royals wins APRA Silver Scroll award|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11140589|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 October 2013|date=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2014Grammys\" /> In [[72nd Golden Globe Awards|2015]], she received a Golden Globe nomination for Best Original Song as a songwriter for \"Yellow Flicker Beat\".<ref name=\"2015GoldenGlobes\"/> Her second studio album ''Melodrama'' received a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards|60th ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/60th-annual-grammy-awards|title=60th Annual Grammy Awards|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> Lorde has received two [[Brit Awards]] for [[Brit Award for International Female Solo Artist|International Female Solo Artist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/feb/19/lorde-wins-international-solo-female-artist-2014-brits |title=Lorde wins international female solo artist award at 2014 Brits |work=The Guardian |first=Tshepo |last=Mokoena |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=19 February 2014}}<br>\n{{cite news|last1=Beaumont-Thomas|first1=Ben|title=Brit awards nominations 2018: Dua Lipa beats Ed Sheeran with five|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/13/brit-awards-nominations-2018-dua-lipa-ed-sheeran|accessdate=13 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=13 January 2018}}</ref> The singer has also won two [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], one [[MTV Video Music Award]] and three [[World Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PpI4xmDF?url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/bbma-2014/6092028/billboard-music-awards-winners-list-complete-full|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/bbma-2014/6092028/billboard-music-awards-winners-list-complete-full|title=Billboard Music Awards 2014: Full Winners List|work=Billboard|archivedate=25 May 2014|date=18 May 2014|access-date=22 September 2014|url-status=live}}<br />\n{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1910089/lorde-vma-best-rock-video/|title=Lorde Becomes First Female Artist To Win Best Rock Video VMA|first=Craig|last=Flaster|publisher=MTV News|date=24 August 2014|accessdate=22 September 2014}}<br />\n{{cite web|title=World Music Awards 2014: Full list of winners|url=http://www.viasat1.com.gh/vone/news/entertainment.php?postId=2114|publisher=[[Viasat 1]]|accessdate=8 August 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140603175624/http://viasat1.com.gh/vone/news/entertainment.php?postId=2114|archivedate=3 June 2014}}</ref> She has sold over five million albums worldwide as of June 2017<ref>{{cite news |title=Lorde: 'I am basically a witch' |url=https://myaccount.news.com.au/sites/dailytelegraph/subscribe.html?sourceCode=DTWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&mode=premium&dest=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/lifestyle/stellar/lorde-i-felt-the-ghost-of-bowie-watching-over-me/news-story/80ca5f349ef53d9e574015fd930718af&memtype=anonymous |accessdate=8 February 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=3 June 2017 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and 15 million certified single units in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gold and Platinum: Top Artists (Digital Singles) |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=top_tallies&ttt=TAS#search_section |website=Recording Industry Association of America |accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lorde discography|List of songs recorded by Lorde|l2=songs}}\n* ''[[Pure Heroine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Melodrama (Lorde album)|Melodrama]]'' (2017)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[Pure Heroine Tour]] (2013\u20132014)\n* [[Melodrama World Tour]] (2017\u20132018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no | commons=Category:Lorde | b=no | n=no | q=Lorde | s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no | d=Q13476175 | mw=no | display=Lorde}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Lorde}}\n* {{MusicBrainz artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|5941025}}\n\n{{Lorde|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Lorde|Accolades for Lorde]]\n| list =\n{{Brit International Female}}\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year 2010s}}\n{{ConsequenceOfSoundArtistBand}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Music|New Zealand}}\n{{featured article}}\n[[Category:Lorde| ]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand singers]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Art pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Dream pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female pop singers|Lorde]]\n[[Category:New Zealand feminists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Auckland]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:Sex-positive feminists]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Takapuna Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People with synesthesia]]\n[[Category:Album-cover and concert-poster artists]]\n[[Category:Electropop musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|New Zealand singer and songwriter}}\n{{about|the singer|other uses|Lorde (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|Lordi|Lord (disambiguation){{!}}Lord}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Lorde\n| image           = RF 3006 Lorde@Arena Krists Luhaers-5 (35769377251) (cropped).jpg\n| alt             = Lorde performing onstage against a purple background\n| caption         = Lorde performing in June 2017\n| birth_name      = Ella Marija Lani Yelich-O'Connor\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1996|11|7}}\n| birth_place     = [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n| citizenship     = {{hlist|New Zealand|[[Croatia]]}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|record producer}}<!---occupation(s) artist is notable for, \"as given in the lead\", per: [[Template:Infobox_person#Parameters]]--> \n| years_active    = 2009\u2013present\n| relatives      = [[Sonja Yelich]] (mother)\n| awards          = [[List of awards and nominations received by Lorde|Full list]]\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = <!-- Sourced in #Musical style. Please do not add or remove genres without discussion or reliable sources -->{{hlist|[[Electropop]]|[[dream pop]]|[[indie pop]]|[[art pop]]|<!-- See talk page before editing this -->}}\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Joel Little]]|[[Jack Antonoff]]}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Universal Music Group|UMG]]|[[Lava Records|Lava]]|[[Republic Records|Republic]]}}\n| website         = {{url|lorde.co.nz}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ella Marija Lani Yelich-O'Connor''' (born 7 November 1996), known professionally as '''Lorde''' (pronounced \"lord\"), is a New Zealand singer and songwriter.<!--only occupations integral to artist's notability per reliable sources; [[MOS:LEADBIO]]--> Taking inspiration from [[aristocracy (class)|aristocracy]] for her stage name, she is known for employing unconventional musical styles and thoughtful songwriting. Born in the [[Auckland]] suburb of [[Takapuna]] and raised in neighbouring [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]], Lorde expressed interest in performing at local venues in her early teens. She signed with [[Universal Music Group]] in 2009 and collaborated with producer [[Joel Little]] in 2011 to start recording material.\n\nUniversal Music commercially released the pair's first collaborative effort, an [[extended play]] (EP) titled ''[[The Love Club EP|The Love Club]]'', in 2013. The EP's international chart-topping single \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\" helped Lorde rise to prominence. Her debut studio album ''[[Pure Heroine]]'' followed that year and achieved critical and commercial success. The following year, Lorde curated [[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1 (soundtrack)|the soundtrack]] for the 2014 film ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay&nbsp;\u2013 Part 1|The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1]]'' and recorded several tracks, including the single \"[[Yellow Flicker Beat]]\". Her second studio album ''[[Melodrama (Lorde album)|Melodrama]]'' (2017) garnered widespread acclaim and debuted at number one in the United States.\n\nLorde's music is primarily [[electropop]] and contains elements of [[Music genres|subgenres]] such as [[dream pop]] and [[indie-electro]]. [[List of awards and nominations received by Lorde|Her accolades]] include two [[Grammy Awards]], two [[Brit Awards]] and a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination. She appeared in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s list of the most influential teenagers in 2013 and 2014, and the 2014 edition of [[Forbes 30 Under 30|''Forbes'' 30 Under 30]]. In addition to her solo work, she has co-written songs for other artists, including [[Broods]] and [[Bleachers (band)|Bleachers]]. As of June 2017, Lorde has sold over five million albums worldwide.\n\n==Early life==\nElla Marija Lani Yelich-O'Connor was born in [[Takapuna]], [[Auckland]] on 7 November 1996,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehairpin.com/2014/01/here-is-lordes-birth-certificate/|title=Here Is Lorde's Birth Certificate|website=[[The Hairpin]]|date=28 January 2014|first=Emma|last=Carmichael|accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> to poet [[Sonja Yelich]] ({{lang-hr|Sonja Jeli\u0107}}) and civil engineer Vic O'Connor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1847971/lorde-parents-engaged/|title=Lorde's Parents Finally Got Engaged&nbsp;\u2013 After 30 Years|first=Brenna|last=Ehrlich|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=17 June 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> Her mother was born to [[Croats|Croatian]] immigrants from the region of [[Dalmatia]], while her father is of Irish descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/21869-singer-lorde-talks-croatian-heritage|title=Grammy Award Winner Lorde Talks Croatian Heritage|website=Total-croatia-news.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818052331/https://www.total-croatia-news.com/lifestyle/21869-singer-lorde-talks-croatian-heritage|archivedate=18 August 2018}}</ref> They announced their engagement in 2014, after a 30-year relationship,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rothman |first1=Michael |title=Lorde's Parents Engaged, at Last |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/lordes-parents-engaged/story?id=24171630 |accessdate=20 August 2019 |work=ABC News |date=17 June 2014}}</ref> and in 2017, they married in a private ceremony in [[Cheltenham, New Zealand|Cheltenham Beach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://i.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/92299673/lordes-parents-get-married-in-auckland|title=Lorde's parents get married in Auckland|work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>\n\nSecond of four children, she has three siblings: older sister Jerry, younger sister India, and younger brother Angelo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lorde's younger sister makes musical debut|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/lordes-younger-sister-makes-musical-debut-20140121-315t0.html|accessdate=25 January 2014|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=21 January 2014}}</ref> They were raised in the nearby Auckland suburb of [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]].<ref name=\"CoverStory\"/> At age five, she joined a drama group and developed [[public speaking]] skills.<ref name=\"Weiner\" /> As a child, Lorde attended [[Vauxhall School]] and then [[Belmont Intermediate School]] in her early teens.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/north-shore-times/8990736/Singer-now-on-centre-stage|title=Singer now on centre stage: Shore kid makes good at Splendour in the Grass|date=2 August 2013|first=Jess|last=Etheridge|work=North Shore Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053757/http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/north-shore-times/8990736/Singer-now-on-centre-stage|archivedate=21 September 2013}}</ref> Her mother encouraged her to read a range of genres, which Lorde cited as a lyrical influence. More specifically, she cites the [[young adult literature|young adult]] [[dystopian]] novel ''[[Feed (Anderson novel)|Feed]]'' (2002) by [[Matthew Tobin Anderson|M.T. Anderson]] as well as authors [[J.D. Salinger]], [[Raymond Carver]] and [[Janet Frame]] for influencing her songwriting.<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\">{{cite web|title=Lorde, the year|work=Black Magazine|first=Grant|last=Fell|url=http://www.blackmagazine.co.nz/blk-list/lorde-the-year/|date=30 January 2014|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10433978/Lorde-interview-Dream-Teen.html|title=Lorde interview: Dream Teen|author=McNulty, Bernadette|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=8 November 2013|accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2009\u20132011: Beginnings===\n[[File:Ella Yelich O'Connor.png|thumb|upright|Lorde performing at the Victoria Theatre in Devonport, 2011|alt=A black-and-white photo of Lorde performing. She is seen touching her hair and smiling while looking downwards]]\n\nIn May 2009, Lorde and her friend Louis McDonald won the Belmont Intermediate School annual talent show as a duo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/lorde-returns-to-belmont-intermediate-school-to-judge-talent-show/story-fni0b8dw-1226761816655|title=Lorde returns to Belmont Intermediate School to judge talent show|work=[[Herald Sun]]|date=17 November 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/76Dfyut0H?url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/lorde-returns-to-belmont-intermediate-school-to-judge-talent-show/news-story/fd9f2d49397cd63a45031e9f245da8e8|archivedate=16 February 2019|access-date=17 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> In August that year, Lorde and McDonald made a guest appearance on [[Jim Mora (broadcaster)|Jim Mora]]'s ''Afternoons'' show on [[Radio New Zealand]]. There, they performed [[cover version|covers]] of [[Pixie Lott]]'s \"[[Mama Do (Uh Oh, Uh Oh)]]\" and [[Kings of Leon]]'s \"[[Use Somebody]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Ella Yelich-O'Connor|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/national/programmes/afternoons/audio/2033420/ella-yelich-o%27connor|publisher=Radio New Zealand|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=17 March 2011}}</ref> McDonald's father then sent his recordings of the duo covering \"Mama Do\" and [[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]]'s \"[[Warwick Avenue (song)|Warwick Avenue]]\" to [[Universal Music Group]] (UMG)'s [[A&R]] executive Scott Maclachlan.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> Maclachlan subsequently signed her to UMG for development.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/>\n\nLorde was also part of the Belmont Intermediate School band Extreme; the band placed third in the North Shore Battle of the Bands finals at the Bruce Mason Centre, Takapuna, Auckland on 18 November 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/lorde-at-age-12-performing-with-her-middle-school-band/|title=Watch 12-Year-Old Lorde Wow Crowd with Her Middle School Band|last=Bender|first=Kelli|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=2 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009092853/https://people.com/celebrity/lorde-at-age-12-performing-with-her-middle-school-band/|archivedate=9 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010, Lorde and McDonald formed a duet called \"Ella & Louis\" and performed covers live on a regular basis at local venues, including caf\u00e9s in Auckland and the Victoria Theatre in Devonport.<ref name=\"Brunt\">{{cite book|title=Made in Australia and Aotearoa/New Zealand: Studies in Popular Music|first1=Shelley|last1=Brunt|first2=Geoff|last2=Stahl|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2018|isbn=978-1-317-270-478|page=72}}</ref> In 2011, UMG hired vocal coach [[Frances Dickinson]] to give her singing lessons twice a week for a year.<ref name=\"lordevmusic\"/> During this time, Maclachlan attempted to partner Lorde with several different producers and songwriters, but without success.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_ScottM.html|title=Interview with Scott MacLachlan, manager of Lorde|publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=21 January 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Q1NyPMHr?url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_ScottM.html|archivedate=2 June 2014|first=Jan|last=Blumentrath|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Stuff.co.NZ:newestPop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/culture/performance/8654143/Lorde-NZs-newest-pop-star|title=NZ newest pop star|date=10 May 2013|first=Tom|last=Cardy|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> As she began writing songs, she learned how to \"put words together\" by reading [[short fiction]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-young-lordes-royal-tour-1394049175|title=A Young Lorde's Royal Tour|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|first=Jim|last=Fusilli|date=5 March 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009092846/https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-young-lordes-royal-tour-1394049175|archivedate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nLorde performed her original songs for the first time at the Victoria Theatre in November 2011.<ref name=\"Brunt\"/> In December, Maclachlan paired Lorde with [[Joel Little]], a songwriter, record producer, and former [[Goodnight Nurse]] lead singer. The pair recorded five songs for an [[extended play]] (EP) at Little's Golden Age Studios in [[Morningside, Auckland]], and finished within three weeks.<ref name=\"NZMusician\">{{cite journal|url=https://nzmusician.co.nz/features/joel-little-rings-of-the-lorde/|title=Joel Little&nbsp;\u2013 Rings of the Lorde|first=Richard|last=Thorne|journal=NZ Musician|date=October\u2013November 2013|volume=17|issue=9|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref> While working on her music career, she attended [[Takapuna Grammar School]] from 2010 to 2013, completing [[Year Twelve#New Zealand|Year 12]].<ref name=\"behindsuccess\">{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/89970537/from-devonport-to-diva-the-story-of-lorde-so-far|title=From Devonport to diva: The story of Lorde so far|date=3 March 2017|work=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> She later chose not to return in 2014 to attend [[Year Thirteen#New Zealand|Year 13]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/234418/she's-still-our-lorde,-say-friends|title=She's still our Lorde, say friends|publisher=Radio New Zealand|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u20132015: ''Pure Heroine'' and ''The Hunger Games'' soundtrack===\n[[File:Lorde - Coachella 2014 (06).jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Lorde wears a white crop top and black trousers singing onstage while closing her eyes.|Lorde at the [[Coachella Festival]] in 2014]]\n\nWhen Lorde and Little had finished their first collaborative effort, ''[[The Love Club EP]]'', Maclachlan applauded it as a \"strong piece of music\", but worried if the EP could profit because Lorde was obscure at the time.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> In November 2012, the singer self-released the EP through her [[SoundCloud]] account for free download.<ref name=\"CoverStory\"/> UMG commercially released ''The Love Club'' in March 2013 after it had been downloaded 60,000 times, which signaled that Lorde had attracted a range of audiences.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Qz78eMoL?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/8653616/Lorde-A-Kiwi-music-mystery|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/8653616/Lorde-A-Kiwi-music-mystery|title=Lorde: A Kiwi music mystery|first=Tom|last=Cardy|work=Stuff.co.nz|date=10 May 2013|archivedate=11 July 2014}}</ref> It peaked at number two in New Zealand and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Lorde&titel=The+Love+Club+EP&cat=s|title=The Love Club EP|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\", the EP's single, helped Lorde rise to prominence after it became a critical and commercial success, selling more than 10 million units worldwide.<ref name=\"royalties\">{{cite news|last=Nippert|first=Matt|date=7 November 2014|title=Birthday girl Lorde's earnings estimated at $11m-plus|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11354524|url-status=live|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180730020806/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11354524|archivedate=30 July 2018}}</ref> It charted at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making Lorde, then 16 years old, the youngest artist to earn a number-one single in the United States since [[Tiffany Darwish|Tiffany]] in 1987,<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/10/04/lorde-is-youngest-performer-to-top-billboard-charts-in-26-years/|title=Lorde is Youngest Performer to Top Billboard Charts in 26 Years|first=Tim|last=Newcomb|date=4 October 2013|journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref> and has since been certified [[RIAA certification|diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2018/06/13/there-are-now-over-20-singles-that-have-been-certified-diamond/#3e4d374db4ed|title=There Are Now Over 20 Singles That Have Been Certified Diamond|first=Hugh|last=McIntyre|work=[[Forbes]]|date=13 June 2018|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> The track won two [[Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|56th ceremony]].<ref name=\"2014Grammys\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/01/26/showbiz/grammys-winners-list/index.html|title=Grammys 2014: Winners list|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=27 January 2014|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nLorde's debut studio album ''[[Pure Heroine]]'' containing the single \"Royals\" was released in September 2013 to critical acclaim;<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> it appeared on several year-end album lists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dietz|first1=Jason|title=Music Critic Top 10 Lists|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-ten-albums-of-2013|accessdate=8 January 2018|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|date=4 December 2013}}</ref> The album received considerable attention for its portrayal of suburban teenage disillusionment and critiques of mainstream culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/18614-lorde-pure-heroine/|title=Lorde: Pure Heroine {{!}} Album Reviews|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|first=Lindsay|last=Zoladz|date=3 October 2013|accessdate=8 September 2014}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/06/26/on-melodrama-lorde-learns-how-messy-adulthood-can-be|title=On 'Melodrama', Lorde Learns How Messy Adulthood Can Be|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=26 June 2017|accessdate=1 February 2019|first=Carrie|last=Battan}}<br />{{cite web|first=Joe|last=Zadeh|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/reviews/lorde-pure-heroine|title=Lorde&nbsp;\u2013 Pure Heroine &#124; Reviews|work=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> In the United States, the album exceeded sales of one million copies in February 2014, becoming the first debut album by a female artist since [[Adele]]'s ''[[19 (Adele album)|19]]'' (2008) to achieve the feat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5922997/lordes-pure-heroine-hits-1-million-in-sales |title=Lorde's 'Pure Heroine' Hits 1 Million in Sales |work=Billboard |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304061926/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5922997/lordes-pure-heroine-hits-1-million-in-sales|archivedate=4 March 2014|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=28 February 2014}}</ref> ''Pure Heroine'' earned a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]],<ref name=\"2014Grammys\"/> and has sold four million copies worldwide as of May 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shah |first=Neil |title=Lorde Wonders How Much Fame is Enough |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/lorde-wonders-how-much-fame-is-enough-1494347686 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=9 May 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Three other singles were released from the album: \"[[Tennis Court (song)|Tennis Court]]\" reached number one in New Zealand,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2215|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> while \"[[Team (Lorde song)|Team]]\" charted at number six in the United States,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5915783/pharrell-williams-happy-hits-no-1-on-hot-100 |title=Pharrell Williams' 'Happy' Hits No. 1 On Hot 100 |work=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> and \"[[Glory and Gore]]\" was released exclusively to US radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://headlineplanet.com/home/2014/03/01/lordes-glory-gore-confirmed-next-single/|title=Lorde's 'Glory and Gore' Confirmed As Next Single|website=Headline Planet|date=1 March 2014|first=Brian|last=Cantor|accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Lorde signed a publishing deal with [[Songs Music Publishing]], worth a reported US$2.5&nbsp;million, after a bidding war between companies including [[Sony Music Entertainment]] and her label UMG. The agreement gave the publisher the right to license Lorde's music for films and advertising.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andrew|last=Hampp|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/5785900/lorde-signs-25-million-deal-with-songs-music-publishing-inside-the-lengthy|title=Lorde Signs $2.5 Million Deal with Songs Music Publishing: Inside the Lengthy Bidding War|work=Billboard|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Later that month, Lorde was featured on the [[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Hunger Games: Catching Fire]]'' (2013), performing a cover of [[Tears for Fears]]' 1985 song \"[[Everybody Wants to Rule the World]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunger Games: Catching Fire soundtrack features Coldplay, Lorde and Christina Aguilera |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/10443307/Hunger-Games-Catching-Fire-soundtrack-features-Coldplay-Lorde-and-Christina-Aguilera.html |accessdate=8 February 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 November 2013}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included her on their lists of the most influential teenagers in the world in 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://time100.time.com/2013/11/12/the-16-most-influential-teens-of-2013/|title=Lorde, 17 {{!}} The 16 Most Influential Teens of 2013|journal=Time|first=Mark|last=Metcalfe|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=9 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3486048/most-influential-teens-2014/|title=The 25 Most Influential Teens of 2014|date=13 October 2014|work=Time|accessdate=25 October 2014}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' also placed her on their 2014 edition of [[Forbes 30 Under 30|30 Under 30]]; she was the youngest individual to be featured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/eeel45ehgfg/lorde-17/|title=Lorde, 17|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' featured her on their 21 Under 21 list in 2013,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lipshutz |first1=Jason |title=6. Lorde: 21 Under 21 (2013) |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/5721561/lorde-21-under-21-2013 |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=25 September 2013}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lipshutz |first1=Jason |title=1. Lorde: 21 Under 21 (2014) |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/6244245/lorde-21-under-21-2014 |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=10 September 2014}}</ref> and 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Partridge |first1=Kenneth |title=Billboard's 21 Under 21 2015: Music's Hottest Young Stars |url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/6745079/billboard-21-under-21-2015-hottest-young-stars |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=30 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2014, Lorde performed at festivals including the [[St Jerome's Laneway Festival|Laneway Festival]] in Sydney,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/laneway-festival-in-sydney-gave-us-lorde-and-felt-just-right-20140203-31w22.html|title=Laneway Festival in Sydney gave us Lorde and felt just right|first=Bernard|last=Zuel|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=3 February 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203175430/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/laneway-festival-in-sydney-gave-us-lorde-and-felt-just-right-20140203-31w22.html|archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref> the three South American editions of [[Lollapalooza]]\u2014[[Lollapalooza Chile|Chile]],<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102012134/http://cnnchile.com/noticia/2013/11/01/este-es-el-line-up-definitivo-de-lollapalooza-chile-2014-encabezado-por-arcade-fire-y-red-hot-chili-peppers|url=http://cnnchile.com/noticia/2013/11/01/este-es-el-line-up-definitivo-de-lollapalooza-chile-2014-encabezado-por-arcade-fire-y-red-hot-chili-peppers|archivedate=2 November 2013|date=1 November 2013|title=Esta pasando. Lo estas viendo|publisher=CNN|language=es}}</ref> Argentina,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11227561|title=Lorde joins Lollapalooza line-up|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 March 2014|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> Brazil<ref>{{cite web|first=Reggie|last=Ugwu|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/festivals/6041368/lollapalooza-brazil-2014-phoenix-arcade-fire-lorde-rock-sao-paulo|title=Lollapalooza Brazil 2014: Phoenix, Arcade Fire, Lorde Rock S\u00e3o Paulo|date=8 April 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\u2014and the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella Festival]] in California.<ref>{{cite news|first=Reggie|last=Ugwu|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/coachella-2014-lorde-makes-desert-695863|title=Coachella 2014: Lorde Makes Desert Debut|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=14 April 2014|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> She subsequently embarked on an [[Pure Heroine Tour|international concert tour]], commencing in North America in early 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5839820/lorde-announces-north-american-tour-dates|title=Lorde Announces North American Tour Dates|date=16 December 2013|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|accessdate=9 September 2014|work=Billboard}}</ref> Amidst her solo activities, Lorde joined the surviving members of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] to perform \"[[All Apologies]]\" during the band's induction ceremony at the [[Rock N' Roll Hall of Fame]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6049353/nirvana-joined-by-joan-jett-kim-gordon-st-vincent-lorde-at-rock-hall-ceremony|title=Nirvana Joined By Joan Jett, Kim Gordon, St. Vincent, Lorde at Rock Hall Ceremony|date=11 April 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=9 May 2014}}</ref> Band members [[Krist Novoselic]] and [[Dave Grohl]] explained that they selected Lorde because her songs represented \"Nirvana aesthetics\" for their perceptive lyrics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/04/dave-grohl-on-lorde-she-represents-the-nirvana-aesthetic-amid-all-that-stripper-pop/|title=Dave Grohl on Lorde: she represents the 'Nirvana aesthetic' amid 'all that stripper pop'|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=26 April 2014|first=Chris|last=Coplan|accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref> Lorde also curated the accompanying [[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1 (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] for ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1]]'' (2014), overseeing the collation of the album's content as well as recording four tracks, including its lead single \"[[Yellow Flicker Beat]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/6289238/lorde-hunger-games-soundtrack-kanye-west|title=Lorde's 'Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Pt. 1' Soundtrack to Feature Kanye West, Chvrches, Charli XCX|first=Zach|last=Dionne|work=Billboard|date=21 October 2014|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> In 2015, the track earned Lorde a [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref name=\"2015GoldenGlobes\">{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Joe|title=2015 Golden Globe Nominees: Lorde, Lana Del Rey, Trent Reznor & More|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6405535/2015-golden-globe-nominees-lorde-lana-del-rey-trent-reznor|accessdate=13 December 2014|work=Billboard|date=11 December 2014}}</ref> Later that year, she was featured on British electronic duo [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]]'s song \"[[Magnets (song)|Magnets]]\" off their album ''[[Caracal (album)|Caracal]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/sep/27/disclosure-caracal-review-dance-duo-lorde-miguel-sam-smith|title=Disclosure: Caracal review \u2013 dance duo's second is saved by the guests|first=Michael|last=Cragg|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=27 September 2015|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Melodrama''===\n[[File:Lorde Brisbane Nov 2017 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|alt=Lorde playing a sampler onstage wearing a pink dress with bedazzled jewels and a flower crown on her head.|Lorde performing in November 2017]]\nAt the [[2016 Brit Awards]] in February, Lorde and [[David Bowie]]'s final touring band gave a tribute performance of his 1971 song \"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/feb/25/david-bowie-brits-tribute-lorde-duncan-jones|title=David Bowie's son thanks Brits for 'beautiful' tribute by Lorde|work=The Guardian|date=25 February 2016|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> Pianist [[Mike Garson]], a frequent band member for Bowie, explained that Bowie's family and management selected Lorde because he admired her and felt she was \"the future of music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/mar/22/david-bowie-lorde-future-of-music|title=David Bowie saw Lorde as 'the future of music'|work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2016|accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref> Later that year, Lorde co-wrote \"[[Heartlines]]\", a song by New Zealand music duo [[Broods]] from their album ''[[Conscious (Broods album)|Conscious]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7401141/lorde-broods-heartlines-co-wrote|title=Lorde Returns! Hear 'Heartlines,' the Song She Co-Wrote With Broods|first=Joe|last=Lynch|work=Billboard|date=10 June 2016|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe lead single from her second studio album ''[[Melodrama (Lorde album)|Melodrama]]'', \"[[Green Light (Lorde song)|Green Light]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39143565|title=All you need to know about Lorde's new single, Green Light|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2 March 2017|accessdate=2 March 2017|author=Savage, Mark}}</ref> was released in March 2017 to widespread acclaim; several publications ranked it as one of the best songs of the year, ''[[NME Single of the Year|NME]]'' and ''The Guardian'' placing it in the top spot on their respective lists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/22/pazz-jop-the-top-albums-and-singles-of-2017/|title=Pazz & Jop: It's Kendrick's and Cardi's World. We're All Just Living in It|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=22 January 2018|accessdate=10 February 2018}}<br />\n{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/nmes-best-tracks-year-2017-2161431/5/|title=Best Songs of the Year 2017|date=27 November 2017|work=[[NME]]|access-date=4 December 2017}}<br />\n{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/04/the-top-100-tracks-of-2017|title=The top 100 tracks of 2017|work=The Guardian|date=4 December 2017|first=Ben|last=Beaumont-Thomas|accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref> It achieved moderate commercial success, reaching number one in New Zealand, number four in Australia and number nine in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Lorde&titel=Green+Light&cat=s|title=Lorde \u2013 Green Light|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=20 February 2019}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Lorde/chart-history/canadian-hot-100/song/1016733|title=Lorde \u2013 Green Light Chart History \u2013 Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=20 February 2019}}</ref> Later that month, she co-wrote and provided background vocals for American indie pop band [[Bleachers (band)|Bleachers]]'s song \"[[Don't Take the Money]]\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Geslani |first1=Michelle |title=Bleachers and Lorde link up on new song 'Don't Take the Money' \u2014 listen |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/bleachers-and-lorde-link-up-on-new-song-dont-take-the-money-listen/ |accessdate=29 December 2018 |work=Consequence of Sound |date=31 March 2017}}</ref> taken from their album ''[[Gone Now]]'' (2017).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Jack Antonoff Details Bleachers' 'Gone Now' LP |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/jack-antonoff-details-bleachers-gone-now-lp-107182/ |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Rolling Stone |date=14 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn ''Melodrama'', Lorde attempted to showcase her maturity as a songwriter and incorporated her post-breakup introspection.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629174023/http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/music/a9766/lords-new-album-different/|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/music/a9766/lords-new-album-different/|title=Why Lorde's Next Album Will Be 'Totally Different'|first=Lauren|last=Valenti|work=[[Marie Claire]]|date=5 June 2014|archivedate=29 June 2016}}</ref> The album was released in June 2017 and received widespread acclaim; [[Metacritic]] placed it second on their list of the best-received records of 2017 based on inclusions in publications' year-end lists, behind [[Kendrick Lamar]]'s ''[[Damn (Kendrick Lamar album)|Damn]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/critics-pick-top-10-best-albums-of-2017|title=Best of 2017: Music Critic Top 10 Lists|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> It reached number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], earning Lorde her first number one on the chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7842114/lorde-melodrama-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|title=Lorde Earns First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Melodrama'|work=Billboard|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|date=25 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626022349/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7842114/lorde-melodrama-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|archivedate=26 June 2017}}</ref> and on album charts of Australia, Canada and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Lorde/chart-history/canadian-albums|title=Lorde Chart History \u2013 Canadian Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=21 January 2019}}<br />\n{{cite web |title=Charts.org.nz \u2013 Lorde \u2013 Melodrama |url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Lorde&titel=Melodrama&cat=a |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> It earned a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards|60th ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/8096810/grammys-2018-bruno-mars-album-of-the-year|title=Bruno Mars Completes His Big Night by Winning Album of the Year for '24K Magic' at the 2018 Grammy Awards|work=Billboard|last=Lamarre|first=Carl|date=28 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319062911/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/8096810/grammys-2018-bruno-mars-album-of-the-year|archivedate=19 March 2018}}</ref> Two other singles from the album were released: \"[[Perfect Places]]\" and a remix of \"[[Homemade Dynamite]]\" featuring [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]], [[Post Malone]] and [[SZA (singer)|SZA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/lorde-announces-new-sza-featuring-homemade-dynamite-remix/|title=Lorde Announces New SZA-Featuring \"Homemade Dynamite\" Remix|last=Kim|first=Michelle|date=|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> \n\nTo promote ''Melodrama'', Lorde embarked on an [[Melodrama World Tour|international concert tour]], the first leg of which took place in Europe in late 2017, featuring Khalid as the supporting act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/06/lorde-announces-melodrama-world-tour.html|title=Lorde Announces Melodrama World Tour, New Song Due Out at Midnight|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=8 June 2017|first=Natalia|last=Barr |accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> She later announced the North American leg, held in March 2018, with [[Run the Jewels]], [[Mitski]] and [[Tove Styrke]] as opening acts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stubblebine |first1=Allison |title=Lorde Reveals Run the Jewels, Mitski & Tove Styrke as Support for Melodrama Tour in North America |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7988877/lorde-melodrama-tour-support-run-the-jewels-mitski-tove-styrke-north-america-dates |accessdate=30 May 2018 |work=Billboard |date=4 October 2017}}</ref> A [[Melodrama World Tour#Israel controversy|political controversy]] occurred in December 2017 when Lorde cancelled her scheduled June 2018 concert in Israel following an online campaign by Palestinian solidarity activists supporting the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions]] (BDS) campaign.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beaumont|first1=Peter|title=Lorde cancels Israel concert after pro-Palestinian campaign|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/25/lorde-cancels-israel-concert-after-pro-palestinian-campaign|accessdate=27 December 2017|work=The Guardian|date=25 December 2017}}</ref> While Lorde did not explicitly indicate her reasons for cancelling, she admitted that she had been unaware of the political turmoil there and \"the right decision at this time is to cancel\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lorde-cancels-tel-aviv-concert-after-calls-to-boycott-israel-199358/|title=Lorde Cancels Tel Aviv Concert After Calls to Boycott Israel|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|date=24 December 2017|work=Rolling Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827210017/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lorde-cancels-tel-aviv-concert-after-calls-to-boycott-israel-199358/|archivedate=27 August 2018}}</ref> Pro-Palestine groups welcomed her decision,<ref>{{cite news|title=Lorde's artistic right to cancel gig in Tel Aviv|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/05/lordes-artistic-right-to-cancel-gig-in-tel-aviv|accessdate=10 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=5 January 2018}}</ref> while pro-Israel groups were critical of the cancellation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lorde called a bigot over cancelled Israel concert in full-page Washington Post ad|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/01/lorde-called-a-bigot-over-israel-stance-in-full-page-washington-post-ad|accessdate=1 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2018}}</ref> ''Billboard'' included Lorde on their 2017 edition of 21 Under 21.<ref>{{cite news |title=21 Under 21 2017: Music's Next Generation |url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/7980786/21-under-21-shawn-mendes-lorde-khalid-camila |accessdate=17 March 2019 |work=Billboard |date=28 September 2017}}</ref> In November 2018, Lorde became a patron of MusicHelps (formerly the New Zealand Music Foundation), a musical charity helping New Zealanders who are vulnerable to or experiencing serious health issues.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lorde becomes patron of MusicHelps, a musical charity helping Kiwis in need |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2018/11/lorde-becomes-patron-of-musichelps-a-musical-charity-helping-kiwis-in-need.html |accessdate=23 May 2019 | publisher=[[Newshub]] |date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Influences===\n{{multiple image\n| footer = Lorde's influences include [[David Bowie]] (left) and [[Robyn]] (right).<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\"/>\n| image1 = David Bowie - Zagreb.jpg\n| alt1   = An image of a man performing onstage with an acoustic guitar, wearing a white dress shirt and a black suit vest.\n| width1 = 143\n| image2 = RobynIn2011 cropped.jpg\n| alt    = A close-up image of a woman smiling away from the camera wearing a white bomber jacket and a black blouse.\n| width2 = 160\n| align = right\n}}\nLorde grew up listening to American [[jazz]] and [[soul music|soul]] musicians [[Billie Holiday]], [[Sam Cooke]], [[Etta James]], and [[Otis Redding]], whose music she admires for \"harvesting their suffering.\"<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\"/> She also listened to her parents' favourite records by the likes of [[Cat Stevens]], [[Neil Young]], and [[Fleetwood Mac]] in her early years.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> During production of ''Pure Heroine'', Lorde cited influences from [[electronic music]] producers, including [[SBTRKT]], [[Grimes (musician)|Grimes]],<ref name=\"James\">{{cite news|title=Lorde&nbsp;\u2013 New Music|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/new-music/10296479/Lorde-New-Music.html|accessdate=14 September 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=11 September 2013|first=James|last=Lachno}}</ref> and [[Sleigh Bells (band)|Sleigh Bells]],<ref>{{cite interview|subject=Lorde|interviewer=[[Lisa Kennedy Montgomery]]|title=Lorde In-Studio with Kennedy|date=20 August 2013|publisher=KYSR|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e2y6H3MCqsk|at=2:58}}</ref> impressed by \"their vocals in a really interesting way, whether it might be chopping up a vocal part or really lash or layering a vocal.\"<ref name=\"lordevmusic\">{{cite web|first=Pip|last=Cowley|url=http://www.vmusic.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/interviews/lorde-q-a|title=Lorde Q&A|publisher=V Music Australia|accessdate=16 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408133117/http://www.vmusic.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/interviews/lorde-q-a|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpostroyals\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/24/lorde-interview_n_3644831.html|title=Lorde, 16-Year-Old New Zealand Musician, Talks 'Royals' Video, Feminism And More|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=30 January 2014|first=Noah|last=Michelson}}</ref> Lorde also stated that she was inspired by the initially hidden identities of [[Burial (musician)|Burial]] and [[The Weeknd]], explaining, \"I feel like mystery is more interesting.\"<ref name=\"CoverStory\"/> Other inspirations include [[Grace Jones]],<ref name=\"Lorde\">{{cite web|author=Julie Naughton and Pete Born|title=Lorde on Influences&nbsp;\u2013 and Cosmetics|date=20 May 2014|work=Women's Wear Daily|url=http://wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/people/lorde-on-influences-and-cosmetics-7688319/|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref> [[James Blake (musician)|James Blake]], [[Yeasayer]], [[Animal Collective]], [[Bon Iver]],<ref name=\"TeenVogue\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/entertainment/music/2013-07/lorde-interview|title=Get to Know Lorde, the 16-Year-Old Pop Star Everyone's Talking About|first=Casey|last=Lewis|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> [[The Smiths]],<ref name=\"huffpostroyals\"/> [[Arcade Fire]],<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\"/> [[Laurie Anderson]],<ref name=\"Weiner\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lordes-teenage-dream-20131028|title=Lorde: The Rise of Pop's Edgiest Teen|first=Jonah|last=Weiner|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=28 October 2013|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> [[Kanye West]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]],<ref name=DigitalSpycoUKintimidatingPeers>{{cite web|url=http://DigitalSpy.co.UK/music/news/a529048/lorde-i-relate-to-kanye-west-and-i-feel-intimidated-by-teenage-girls.html|title=Lorde 'I relate to Kanye West and I feel intimidated by teenage girls'|date=5 November 2013|last=Simpson|first=Leah|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref> and David Bowie.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/lorde-reveals-david-bowie-inspiration-second-album-new-single/|title=Lorde reveals David Bowie was inspiration for second album as new single Green Light released|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=21 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nLyrically, Lorde cited her mother, a poet, as the primary influence for her songwriting.<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> She also named several authors, including [[Kurt Vonnegut]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boardman |first1=Madeline |title=Lorde On Her Inspirations, Style, And Rise To Fame |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/16/lorde-inspirations-style-rise-to-fame_n_4611442.html |website=HuffPost |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126172712/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/16/lorde-inspirations-style-rise-to-fame_n_4611442.html|archivedate=26 November 2014 |date=16 January 2014}}</ref> [[Raymond Carver]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\">{{cite web|last=Selby|first=Jenn|url=https://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/article/lorde-royals-pure-heroine-interview-music-videos|title=Lorde Royals Pure Heroine Interview|work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|date=28 October 2013|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> [[Wells Tower]],<ref name=\"iheartradionz\">{{cite interview|subject=Lorde|interviewer=[[Polly Gillespie]]|title=ZMTV&nbsp;\u2013 Lorde Interview (Polly Speaks to Lorde Before The iHeartRadio NZ Launch)|date=18 September 2013|publisher=ZM|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cir4TKJlupA|at=2:18}}</ref> [[Tobias Wolff]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\"/> [[Claire Vaye Watkins]],<ref name=\"iheartradionz\"/> [[Sylvia Plath]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\"/> [[Walt Whitman]],<ref name=\"influencesglamour\"/> and [[T. S. Eliot]] as lyrical inspirations, particularly noting their [[sentence structure]]s.<ref name=\"James\"/> When writing her second album, ''Melodrama'', Lorde took inspiration from the melodic styles of a variety of musicians, including [[Phil Collins]],<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\"/> [[Don Henley]],<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/12/magazine/the-return-of-lorde.html|title=The Return of Lorde|first=Jonah|last=Weiner|date=12 April 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> [[Tom Petty]],<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\">{{cite web|last1=Mackay |first1=Emily |title=Lorde talks fame, growing up and her new album 'Melodrama' \u2013 NME |url=http://www.nme.com/features/lorde-interview-2017-melodrama-nme-2088564 |website=NME |accessdate=19 June 2017 |date=16 June 2017}}</ref> [[Joni Mitchell]],<ref name=\"TheGuardianProfile\"/> [[Leonard Cohen]],<ref name=\"TheGuardianProfile\">{{cite news|last1=Lamont|first1=Tom|title=Lorde: 'I want to be Leonard Cohen. I want to be Joni Mitchell'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/17/lorde-singer-songwriter-music-royals-tom-lamont|accessdate=23 February 2018|work=The Guardian|date=17 June 2017}}</ref> and [[Robyn]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Lorde Uses Robyn's 'Dancing On My Own' as Studio Inspiration|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6560649/lorde-robyn-dancing-on-my-own-studio-next-album|accessdate=23 February 2018|work=Billboard|date=7 May 2015}}</ref> During the recording process, Lorde stated that [[Frank Ocean]]'s 2016 album ''[[Blonde (Frank Ocean album)|Blonde]]'' inspired her to eschew \"traditional song structures.\"<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\"/> She frequently listened to [[Paul Simon]]'s 1986 album ''[[Graceland (Paul Simon album)|Graceland]]'' while riding subways in [[New York City]] and on taxi rides on the way home from parties in her hometown of Auckland.<ref name=\"NewsweekMelodramaInspirations\">{{cite news|last1=Shaffer|first1=Claire|title=The Influences on Lorde's 'Melodrama': Frank Ocean, Robyn, Bowie and 10 Other Artists Who Shaped Its Sound|url=http://www.newsweek.com/lorde-melodrama-influences-frank-ocean-robyn-bowie-prince-628768|accessdate=23 February 2018|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=24 June 2017}}</ref> She cited the science fiction short story \"[[There Will Come Soft Rains (short story)|There Will Come Soft Rains]]\" (1950) by [[Ray Bradbury]] as inspiration for much of ''Melodrama''{{'s}} story, relating it to her own realities she faced.<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/>\n\n===Musical style and songwriting===\n{{Listen\n| filename = Royals Lorde.ogg\n| title = \"Royals\" (2013)\n| description = Lorde's debut studio album ''Pure Heroine'' was noted for its minimalist production, exemplified by the [[art pop]] and [[electropop]] single \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\".<ref name=\"spin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/12/best-songs-2013/131125-best-songs-lorde/|title=50 Best Songs of 2013: No. 15&nbsp;\u2013 Lorde: 'Royals'|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR\"/><ref name=\"PureHeroineConsequence\"/>\n| format = [[Ogg]]\n| pos = right\n}}\nIn an interview with ''[[NME]]'' in 2017, Lorde declared \"I don\u2019t think about staying in my genre lane\".<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] characterised her style as primarily [[electropop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/lorde-mn0003085111/biography|title=Lorde Biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|first=Stephen|last=Thomas Erlewine|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> Upon the release of ''Pure Heroine'', contemporary critics described her music as electropop,<ref name=\"PureHeroineConsequence\"/> [[art pop]],<ref name=\"GlobeAndMail\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/album-reviews/in-an-age-of-manufactured-stars-lorde-is-a-refreshing-change/article14678181/|title=In an age of manufactured stars, Lorde is a refreshing change|first=Brad|last=Wheeler|date=7 October 2013|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> [[dream pop]],<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/175719-lorde-pure-heroine-2495719039.html|title=Lorde: Pure Heroine|first=Evan|last=Sawdey|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=10 October 2013|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> [[indie pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/artists/31696-lorde/|title=Lorde|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=4 February 2019|quote=Melodrama [...] told the story of a single party, and advanced her indie-pop sound into synesthetic revelry}}</ref> and [[indie-electro]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mahoney|first=Stan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/australia-culture-blog/2014/jul/09/lorde-review-voice-of-the-generation-with-a-dash-of-gold-lame-and-confetti|title=Lorde review&nbsp;\u2013 voice of the generation, with a dash of gold lam\u00e9 and confetti|work=The Guardian|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> Critics also noted the influence of [[hip hop music|hip hop]] on the album's song structures,<ref name=\"PH_reviews\">{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17931/reviews/4147053|title=Album Review: Lorde \u2013 Pure Heroine|work=[[Drowned in Sound]]|first=Sammy|last=Maine|date=28 October 2013|accessdate=1 February 2019}}<br />{{cite web |last=Interrante |first=Scott |title=Gold Teeth, White Teeth, and Lorde's 'Pure Heroine' |url=https://www.popmatters.com/175777-gold-teeth-white-teeth-and-lordes-pure-heroine-2495718477.html |accessdate=4 June 2018 |work=PopMatters |date=17 October 2013}}</ref> as well as its unconventional pop sound and minimalist production.<ref name=\"NPR\"/> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' pointed that the minimal production of ''Pure Heroine'' \"allows [her] to sing any melody she wants, layering them over one another to create a [[chorus effect|choral effect]]\".<ref name=\"PureHeroineConsequence\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2013/09/album-review-lorde-pure-heroine/|title=Lorde&nbsp;\u2013 Pure Heroine {{!}} Album Review|work=Consequence of Sound|date=30 September 2013|first=Jon|last=Hadusek|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> ''Melodrama'' was a departure from the hip hop-oriented minimalist style of its predecessor, incorporating [[piano]] instrumentation and [[maximalism#music|maximalist]] electronic beats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/album-review-lorde-melodrama/|title=Lorde \u2013 Melodrama|work=Consequence of Sound|last=Weiss|first=Dan|date=19 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105011419/https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/album-review-lorde-melodrama/|archivedate=5 January 2018}}<br />{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/18/lorde-melodrama-review-maximum-overwrought-green-light-liability|title=Lorde: Melodrama review \u2013 maximum overwrought|last=Empire|first=Kitty|date=18 June 2017|work=The Guardian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223014704/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/jun/18/lorde-melodrama-review-maximum-overwrought-green-light-liability|archivedate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nLorde utilises her vocals and does not play musical instruments on her records or onstage, elaborating, \"[My] voice needs to have the focus. My vocal-scape is really important\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/21/arts/music/mutual-admiration-across-the-sea-across-the-years.html|title=Mutual Admiration, Across the Sea, Across the Years|first=Melena|last=Ryzik|date=20 May 2014|work=The New York Times|accessdate=16 June 2014}}<br />{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/meet-lorde-shes-a-talented-teenage-badass|title=Meet Lorde: She's a Talented Teenage Badass|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|first=Liza|last=Darwin|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' described Lorde's vocals as \"unique and powerfully intriguing\",<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> while ''Billboard'' characterised her voice as \"dynamic, smoky and restrained\".<ref name=\"BillboardTrackByTrack\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5733177/lorde-pure-heroine-track-by-track-review|title=Lorde, 'Pure Heroine' Track-By-Track Review|date=25 September 2013|work=Billboard|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' wrote that Lorde's voice \"is the alpha and omega of her talent\", characterising it as \"mystifying and alluring\" that harmonised well with the electronic production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/lorde-ipure-heroinei-103883|title=Lorde: Pure Heroine \u2013 Music Review|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|first=Kevin|last=McFarland|date=8 October 2013|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' noted that her songs incorporated the [[mixolydian mode]], a melodic structure used in \"[[blues]]-based and [[alternative rock]]\" music, which set her songs apart from those in pop music for not fitting a common [[major chord|major]] or [[minor chord|minor]] chord.<ref>{{cite news|last=Witmer|first=Phil|title=Here's the Music Theory Behind Why Lorde's Songwriting Is Objectively Kickass|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/wnk57n/heres-why-lordes-songwriting-is-objectively-kickass|accessdate=5 January 2018|work=Vice|date=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nRegarding her songwriting process, Lorde explained that the foundation to her songs began with the lyrics, which could sometimes stem from a singular word meant to summarise a specific idea she had tried to identify.<ref name=\"BlackMagazine\"/> For \"Tennis Court\", Lorde wrote the music before lyrics.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Lorde|year=2013|title=Lyrical Influences (VEVO LIFT): Brought to You By McDonald's|medium=video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zCSFHsd7NWA|accessdate=22 November 2013|publisher=VEVO/YouTube|time=1:49|quote=I think my writing process with 'Tennis Court' was quite different to how I normally write. Generally, I will have a lyric forming before I go into the studio. But with this one, we wrote the music and beat before we wrote anything lyrically}}</ref> She stated that the songwriting on ''Pure Heroine'' developed from the perspective of an observer.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/> Similarly, in an interview with ''NME'', Lorde acknowledged that she used words of inclusion (such as \"we\" and \"us\") throughout her debut album, while her follow-up ''Melodrama'' presented a shift to [[first-person narrative]], employing more introspective lyrics inspired by Lorde's personal struggles post-breakup and viewpoints on post-teenage maturity.<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/> Lorde's neurological condition [[chromesthesia]] influenced her songwriting on the album; it led her to arrange colours according to each song's theme and emotion.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/>\n\n==Public image==\n[[File:Lorde - Coachella 2014 (07).jpg|thumb|upright|Lorde is known for her unchoreographed dancing onstage, which has polarised audiences.|alt=Lorde performing onstage with spontaneous and unchoreographed moves, wearing a blazer and white sneakers]]\nLorde's stage name bears her fascination with \"[[royal family|royals]] and [[aristocracy (class)|aristocracy]]\"; she added an \"e\" after the name Lord, which she felt was too masculine, to make it more feminine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/08/lorde-101-who-is-this-16-year-old-singer.html|title=Lorde 101: Who Is This 16-Year-Old New Zealand Singer Everyone's Talking About?|first=Lindsey|last=Weber|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=19 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821231605/https://www.vulture.com/2013/08/lorde-101-who-is-this-16-year-old-singer.html|archivedate=21 August 2013|access-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She described her public image as something that \"naturally\" came to her and was identical to her real life personality.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sarah|last=Harvey|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/9561880/Lorde-keeps-it-real-about-sex-appeal|title=Lorde keeps it real about sex appeal|website=Stuff.co.nz|date=29 December 2013|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> Lorde is a self-identified [[Feminism|feminist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11151243|title=Lorde says sex on stage the next step for pop stars|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=4 November 2013|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref> ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' opined that her feminist ideology was different from her contemporaries due to Lorde's disinterest in sexualised performances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11194512|title=Lorde makes feminism a class issue|first=Rosemary|last=Overell|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=31 January 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140131193902/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11194512|archivedate=31 January 2014|access-date=6 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The singer proclaimed herself in an interview with ''[[V (American magazine)|V]]'' as a \"hugely [[sex-positive movement|sex-positive]] person\", saying, \"I have nothing against anyone getting naked.&nbsp;... I just don't think it really would complement my music in any way or help me tell a story any better\".<ref name=\"varietyinterview\">{{cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/praise-the-lorde/|title=Praise the Lorde|work=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|first=William|last=Defebaugh|date=16 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009092638/https://vmagazine.com/article/praise-the-lorde/|archivedate=9 October 2018|access-date=9 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCritical reception of Lorde is generally positive, praise concentrated on her maturity both musically and lyrically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/lorde-review-star-shines-under-the-burden-of-expectation-20171122-gzq9gc.html|title=Lorde review: Star shines under the burden of expectation|first=George|last=Palathingal|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=22 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203043309/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/lorde-review-star-shines-under-the-burden-of-expectation-20171122-gzq9gc.html|archivedate=3 February 2019|access-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' called her \"the pop prodigy\" who was not conformed to boundaries and always sought experimentation.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimesProfile\"/> ''Billboard'' recognised Lorde as a spokesperson for a \"female rock resurgence\" by introducing her works to rock and alternative radio, which had seen a traditional male dominance.<ref name=\"billboardalternative\">{{cite news |last=Trust |first=Gary |title=Lorde, HAIM Bring Girl Power To Alternative |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5755301/lorde-haim-bring-girl-power-to-alternative |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Billboard |date=11 October 2013}}</ref> The publication also named her the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|New Queen of Alternative]]\" in a 2013 cover story.<ref name=\"CoverStory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5687161/lorde-the-billboard-cover-story|title=Lorde: The Billboard Cover Story|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|date=6 September 2013|accessdate=20 June 2014}}</ref> Journalist [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic towards Lorde's styles, labelling the singer as \"a pop property\" that was indistinguishable from other mainstream artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Lorde|title=Lorde|first=Robert|last=Christgau|authorlink=Robert Christgau|publisher=Robert Christgau Consumer Guide|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703050859/https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Lorde|archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nLorde's critiques of mainstream culture on ''Pure Heroine'' earned her the title \"the voice of [[Millennials|her generation]]\",<ref name=\"telegraph1\"/> a label she dismissed, saying that \"young people have never needed a specialised spokesperson\".<ref name=\"NMEMelodrama\"/> [[Jon Caramanica]], writing for ''The New York Times'', credited Lorde for bringing forth a \"wave of female rebellion\" to mainstream audiences that embraced an \"anti-pop\" sentiment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/arts/music/in-lordes-wake-a-groundswell-of-female-rebels-in-pop.html|title=In Lorde's Wake, a Groundswell of Female Rebels in Pop|first=Jon|last= Caramanica|date=30 August 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> Sharing a similar viewpoint, an [[op-ed]] of ''Vice'' recognised the singer as the reformer for the teenage pop scene, shifting from [[Britney Spears]]'s renowned [[bubblegum pop]] to modern-day \"mainstream melancholy\" and \"millennial darkness\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/rdz7ay/britney-vs-lorde-a-case-study|title=The Shifting Image of the Teenage Female Pop Star: How We Got from Britney Spears to Lorde|work=Vice|first=Aliza |last=Abarbanel|date=30 May 2015|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' and [[NPR]] credited her debut studio album ''Pure Heroine'' as the foundation of that transformation.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/08/31/638897130/lorde-is-the-21st-centurys-author-of-adolescent-evolution|title=Lorde Is The 21st Century's Author Of Adolescent Evolution|first=Cyrena|last=Tourous|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=31 August 2018|accessdate=21 January 2018}}<br />{{cite web|last=Morris |first=Alex |title=Lorde's Growing Pains: How Pop's Favorite Outsider Wrote Her Next Chapter |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lordes-growing-pains-how-pops-favorite-outsider-wrote-her-next-chapter-127944/ |accessdate=14 December 2018 |work=Rolling Stone |date=15 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHer onstage persona, particularly her signature unchoreographed dancing, has polarised audiences. Her detractors have described her dance moves as \"awkward\" in comparison to contemporary stage performers.<ref>\n{{cite web|last1=Newshub Staff|title=Lorde hits back at critics of her SNL dance|url=http://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2017/03/lorde-hits-back-at-critics-of-her-snl-dance.html|accessdate=8 February 2018|publisher=Newshub|date=14 March 2017}}<br />\n{{cite web|last1=Rosen|first1=Christopher|title=Lorde defends controversial VMAs performance|url=http://ew.com/music/2017/09/10/lorde-defends-vmas/|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=10 September 2017}}<br />\n{{cite news|last1=Meltzer|first1=Marisa|title=For a Power Girl, Cheers and Disses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/fashion/Lorde-Ella-Yelich-OConnor-Grammy.html|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=The New York Times|date=7 February 2014}}<br />\n{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/76GoMheqj?url=http://time.com/4700910/lorde-on-snl-dancing-criticism/|url=http://time.com/4700910/lorde-on-snl-dancing-criticism/|title=Lorde Hits Back at Criticism of Her Saturday Night Live Dancing|first=Megan|last=McCluskey|work=Time|date=14 March 2017|archivedate=18 February 2019|access-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}\n</ref> ''[[The Fader]]'' expressed that she should be celebrated for her dancing as it is \"more freeform and spontaneous\" than structured choreography and \"speaks an entirely different expressive language\". The publication further elaborated that her \"stage presence [is] more impactful than the average pop performance\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cliff|first1=Aimee|title=Why Lorde Is A Great Dancer|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/04/25/lorde-dancing-green-light-snl-coachella|accessdate=8 February 2018|work=[[The Fader]]|date=25 April 2017}}</ref> Lorde's works have directly influenced several contemporary artists, including [[Amanda Palmer]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Axeman |first1=Stephen |title=Amanda Palmer on \u201cThere Will Be No Intermission\u201d |url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/interviews/amanda_palmer_on_there_will_be_no_intermission/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Under the Radar |date=6 May 2019}}</ref> [[Amandla Stenberg]],<ref name=\"rsinfluence\">{{cite news |last1=Spanos |first1=Brittany |title=18 Teens Shaking Up Pop Culture |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/18-teens-shaking-up-pop-culture-11682/amandla-stenberg-16-228496/ |accessdate=27 May 2019 |work=Rolling Stone |date=16 September 2015}}</ref> [[Charly Bliss]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Jonathan |title=How Charly Bliss Learned to Love Pop |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/charly-bliss-young-enough-interview-835213/ |accessdate=19 May 2019 |work=Rolling Stone |date=17 May 2019}}</ref> [[Conan Gray]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Caitlin |title=Conan Gray Writes Intimate, Practically Perfect Pop Songs Inspired By Lorde, Taylor Swift, And Adele |url=https://uproxx.com/pop/conan-gray-primer/ |accessdate=7 September 2019 |work=Uproxx |date=4 September 2019}}</ref> [[Courtney Love]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Trendell |first1=Andrew |title=Courtney Love on her new album: 'It'll have beats. Like Lorde has beats' |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/courtney-love-discusses-autobiography-new-album-inspired-lorde-lana-del-rey-2068589 |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=NME |date=9 May 2017}}</ref> [[Fletcher (singer)|Fletcher]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Selzer |first1=Jillian |title=Fletcher Debuts New Power Ballad \"Wasted Youth,\" Interview |url=https://vmagazine.com/article/premiere-fletcher-debuts-new-power-ballad-wasted-youth/ |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=V |date=26 August 2016}}</ref> [[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Weatherby |first=Taylor |title=James Bay Explains How Lorde, Frank Ocean & David Bowie Played Into His 'Evolving' Sound For New Single 'Wild Love' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8098843/james-bay-wild-love-interview-new-song |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Billboard |date=8 February 2018}}</ref> Khalid,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Holden |first1=Steve |title=Why Khalid loves Fleetwood Mac and Sir Elton John |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/41610461/why-khalid-loves-fleetwood-mac-and-sir-elton-john |accessdate=14 December 2018 |publisher=BBC |date=13 October 2017}}</ref> [[K.Flay]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Takeover Tuesday Playlist: K.Flay Picks Her Favorite Lyrics From Lorde, Cage the Elephant & More |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8523498/kflay-playlist-takeover-tuesday |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Billboard |date=23 July 2019}}</ref> [[Nina Nesbitt]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Sabrina |title=Nina Nesbitt Talks New Single, Songwriting and Being a DIY Female Producer: Interview |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7865864/nina-nesbitt-the-moments-im-missing-songwriting-diy-female-producer |accessdate=3 June 2018 |work=Billboard |date=14 July 2017}}</ref> [[Sigrid (singer)|Sigrid]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Longo |first1=Joseph |title=Don't Kill Sigrid's Vibe: Scandinavia's Breakout Pop Sensation on Her Debut Album 'Sucker Punch' |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/dont-kill-sigrids-vibe-scandinavias-breakout-pop-sensation-on-her-debut-album-sucker-punch |accessdate=30 September 2019 |work=The Daily Beast |date=9 March 2019}}</ref> [[Tavi Gevinson]],<ref name=\"rsinfluence\"/> [[Tessa Violet]],<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |title=Why We're Infatuated with Tessa Violet |url=https://thefullest.com/2018/08/07/why-were-infatuated-with-tessa-violet/ |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=The Fullest |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> [[The Aces (indie pop band)|The Aces]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cirisano |first1=Tatiana |title=Chartbreaker: Pop-Rock Quartet The Aces Were Inspired By Lorde To Get Serious |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8070475/the-aces-stuck-interview-chartbreaker |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=Billboard |date=15 December 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Tove Lo]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tanzer |first1=Miles |title=How Tove Lo got really weird and made the best album of her career |url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/12/05/tove-lo-blue-lips-interview-disco-tits |accessdate=14 December 2018 |work=The Fader |date=5 December 2017}}</ref> [[Troye Sivan]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeRosa |first1=Nicole |title=Q&A with Troye Sivan |url=https://music.allaccess.com/qa-with-troye-sivan/ |accessdate=26 May 2019 |publisher=AllAccess.com |date=22 April 2016}}</ref> and [[Yungblud]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scrudato |first1=Ken |title=BlackBook Interview with Brit Rocker Yungblud and His Guide to Authentic, Indie London |url=https://bbook.com/nightlife/interview-w-brit-rocker-yungblud-guide-authentic-indie-london/ |accessdate=6 October 2019 |work=BlackBook |publisher=Vibe |date=9 February 2018}}</ref> She placed at number 12 on NPR's 2018 readers poll of the most influential female musicians of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |last=Lorusso |first=Marissa |title=Turning the Tables: Your List Of The 21st Century's Most Influential Women Musicians |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/20/668372321/turning-the-tables-your-list-of-the-21st-centurys-most-influential-women-musicia |accessdate=14 December 2018 |publisher=NPR |date=20 November 2018}}</ref> Lorde was parodied in the ''[[South Park]]'' episodes \"[[The Cissy]]\" and \"[[Rehash (South Park)|Rehash]]\", broadcast in October and December 2014, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6281319/lorde-south-park-spin-cissy|title=Watch Lorde Return to 'South Park' & See Her Reaction|work=Billboard|first=Chris|last=Payne|date=9 October 2014|accessdate=3 February 2019}}<br />{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/12/south-park-mocks-music-industry-with-lorde-and-tupac-holograms-watch/|title=South Park mocks music industry with Lorde and Tupac holograms \u2013 watch|date=4 December 2014|work=Consequence of Sound|accessdate=3 February 2019|first=Alex|\nlast=Young}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom late 2013 to early 2016, Lorde was in a relationship with New Zealand photographer James Lowe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roxborough|first=Scott|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6028981/lordes-boyfriend-on-singers-accomplishments-i-couldnt-be-prouder|title=Lorde's Boyfriend on Singer's accomplishments: 'I Couldn't Be Prouder'|date=27 March 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=9 September 2014}}<br>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/celebrities/75984352/Reports-Lorde-has-split-from-her-boyfriend-James-Lowe-after-three-years|title=Reports: Lorde has split from her boyfriend James Lowe after three years|date=19 January 2016|accessdate=14 March 2018|website=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref> In January 2016, she relocated from Devonport to [[Herne Bay, New Zealand|Herne Bay]], an affluent suburb in Auckland, where she purchased a NZ$2.84 (USD$2.01) million home.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11574655|title=Lorde pays $2.84m for her city villa|date=16 January 2016|newspaper=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> She holds both New Zealand and Croatian citizenship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedubrovniktimes.com/news/croatia/item/3053-lorde-reveals-that-she-has-croatian-citizenship|title=Lorde reveals that she has Croatian citizenship|last=Thomas|first=Mark|date=8 September 2017|work=The Dubrovnik Times|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Lorde}}\nAfter her breakthrough, Lorde won four [[New Zealand Music Awards]] at the [[2013 New Zealand Music Awards|2013 ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lorde wins big at 2013 NZ Music Awards|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Lorde-wins-big-at-2013-NZ-Music-Awards/tabid/418/articleID/322318/Default.aspx|accessdate=21 November 2013|work=3 News|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> The single \"Royals\" earned the [[APRA Awards (New Zealand)|APRA Silver Scroll Award]], and two Grammy Awards for Best Pop Solo Performance and Song of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jenkins|first=Lydia|title=Lorde's Royals wins APRA Silver Scroll award|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11140589|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=15 October 2013|date=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2014Grammys\" /> In [[72nd Golden Globe Awards|2015]], she received a Golden Globe nomination for Best Original Song as a songwriter for \"Yellow Flicker Beat\".<ref name=\"2015GoldenGlobes\"/> Her second studio album ''Melodrama'' received a Grammy nomination for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards|60th ceremony]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/60th-annual-grammy-awards|title=60th Annual Grammy Awards|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref> Lorde has received two [[Brit Awards]] for [[Brit Award for International Female Solo Artist|International Female Solo Artist]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/feb/19/lorde-wins-international-solo-female-artist-2014-brits |title=Lorde wins international female solo artist award at 2014 Brits |work=The Guardian |first=Tshepo |last=Mokoena |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=19 February 2014}}<br>\n{{cite news|last1=Beaumont-Thomas|first1=Ben|title=Brit awards nominations 2018: Dua Lipa beats Ed Sheeran with five|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/13/brit-awards-nominations-2018-dua-lipa-ed-sheeran|accessdate=13 January 2018|work=The Guardian|date=13 January 2018}}</ref> The singer has also won two [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]], one [[MTV Video Music Award]] and three [[World Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PpI4xmDF?url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/bbma-2014/6092028/billboard-music-awards-winners-list-complete-full|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/bbma-2014/6092028/billboard-music-awards-winners-list-complete-full|title=Billboard Music Awards 2014: Full Winners List|work=Billboard|archivedate=25 May 2014|date=18 May 2014|access-date=22 September 2014|url-status=live}}<br />\n{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1910089/lorde-vma-best-rock-video/|title=Lorde Becomes First Female Artist To Win Best Rock Video VMA|first=Craig|last=Flaster|publisher=MTV News|date=24 August 2014|accessdate=22 September 2014}}<br />\n{{cite web|title=World Music Awards 2014: Full list of winners|url=http://www.viasat1.com.gh/vone/news/entertainment.php?postId=2114|publisher=[[Viasat 1]]|accessdate=8 August 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140603175624/http://viasat1.com.gh/vone/news/entertainment.php?postId=2114|archivedate=3 June 2014}}</ref> She has sold over five million albums worldwide as of June 2017<ref>{{cite news |title=Lorde: 'I am basically a witch' |url=https://myaccount.news.com.au/sites/dailytelegraph/subscribe.html?sourceCode=DTWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&mode=premium&dest=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/lifestyle/stellar/lorde-i-felt-the-ghost-of-bowie-watching-over-me/news-story/80ca5f349ef53d9e574015fd930718af&memtype=anonymous |accessdate=8 February 2019 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=3 June 2017 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and 15 million certified single units in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gold and Platinum: Top Artists (Digital Singles) |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=top_tallies&ttt=TAS#search_section |website=Recording Industry Association of America |accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lorde discography|List of songs recorded by Lorde|l2=songs}}\n* ''[[Pure Heroine]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Melodrama (Lorde album)|Melodrama]]'' (2017)\n\n==Tours==\n* [[Pure Heroine Tour]] (2013\u20132014)\n* [[Melodrama World Tour]] (2017\u20132018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no | commons=Category:Lorde | b=no | n=no | q=Lorde | s=no | v=no | voy=no | species=no | d=Q13476175 | mw=no | display=Lorde}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Lorde}}\n* {{MusicBrainz artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|5941025}}\n\n{{Lorde|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Lorde|Accolades for Lorde]]\n| list =\n{{Brit International Female}}\n{{Grammy Award for Song of the Year 2010s}}\n{{ConsequenceOfSoundArtistBand}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Music|New Zealand}}\n{{featured article}}\n[[Category:Lorde| ]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand singers]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Art pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Dream pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female pop singers|Lorde]]\n[[Category:New Zealand feminists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Auckland]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women in electroni